/breaking-nigerias-inflation-rate-drops-to-11-37-per-cent-nbs/|title=Breaking: Nigeria\u2019s inflation rate drops to 11.37 per cent \u2013 NBS}}</ref>\n|poverty         = {{plainlist|\n*46% (2009)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SI.POV.NAHC?locations=NG |title=Poverty headcount ratio at national poverty lines (% of population) |publisher=[[World Bank]]|website=data.worldbank.org |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n*77.6% on less than $3.20/day (2009)<ref>{{cite web |title=Poverty headcount ratio at $3.20 a day (2011 PPP) (% of population) - Nigeria |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SI.POV.LMIC?locations=NG&name_desc=false |website=data.worldbank.org |publisher=World Bank |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>}}\n|gini            = 43.0 {{color|darkorange|medium}} (2009, [[World Bank]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SI.POV.GINI?locations=NG |title=GINI index (World Bank estimate) |publisher=[[World Bank]]|website=data.worldbank.org |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n|hdi             = {{plainlist|\n*{{increase}} 0.534 {{color|red|low}} (2018)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hdr.undp.org/en/indicators/137506 |title=Human Development Index (HDI) |publisher=[[Human Development Report|HDRO (Human Development Report Office)]] [[United Nations Development Programme]] |website=hdr.undp.org |access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref> ([[List of countries by Human Development Index|158th]])\n*0.349 {{color|red|low}} [[List of countries by inequality-adjusted HDI|IHDI]] (2018)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/table-3-inequality-adjusted-human-development-index-ihdi |title=Inequality-adjusted Human Development Index (IHDI) |publisher=[[Human Development Report|HDRO (Human Development Report Office)]] [[United Nations Development Programme]] |website=hdr.undp.org |access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref>}}\n|edbr            = {{increase}} [[Ease of doing business index#Ranking|131st (medium, 2020)]]<ref name=\"World Bank and International Financial Corporation\">{{cite web|url= http://www.doingbusiness.org/data/exploreeconomies/nigeria/ |title= Doing Business in Nigeria 2012|publisher=Doing Business,org|access-date=31 January 2017}}</ref>\n|labor           = {{plainlist|\n*{{increase}} 62,447,234 (2019)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SL.TLF.TOTL.IN?locations=NG |title=Labor force, total - Nigeria |publisher=[[World Bank]] |website=data.worldbank.org |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n*{{increase}} 69.9% employment rate (2017)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SL.EMP.TOTL.SP.NE.ZS?locations=NG |title=Employment to population ratio, 15+, total (%) (national estimate) - Nigeria |publisher=[[World Bank]] |website=data.worldbank.org |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>}}\n|occupations     = {{plainlist|\n*[[Lodging|Accommodation]], [[food]], [[transportation]] and [[real estate]]: 12.2%\n*[[Education]], [[health]], [[science]] and [[technology]]: 6.3%\n*[[Farming]], [[forestry]] and [[fishing]]: 30.5%\n*[[Manufacturing]], [[mining]] and [[quarrying]]: 11.3%\n*[[Retail]], [[maintenance, repair, and operations]]: 24.9% \n*Managerial, [[finance]] and [[insurance]]: 4.2%\n*[[Telecommunication]], [[arts]] and [[entertainment]]: 1.8%\n*Other services: 8.8%\n*(2010)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng/pages/download/41 | title=Labour Force Statistics, 2010 | publisher=Nigerian Bureau of Statistics | date=2010 | access-date=22 June 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424153316/http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng/pages/download/41 | archivedate=24 April 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\n|unemployment    = 23.1% (Q3 2018)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/301896-nigerias-unemployment-rate-rises-to-23-1-nbs.html|title=Nigeria\u2019s unemployment rate rises to 23.1% \u2013 NBS|date=2018-12-19|work=Premium Times|access-date=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n|industries      = [[cement]], [[Oil refinery|oil refining]],  [[construction]] and [[construction materials]], [[food processing]] and [[food products]], [[beverages]] and [[tobacco]], [[textile]]s, [[Clothing|apparel]] and [[footwear]], [[Pharmaceutical drug|pharmaceutical products]], [[Engineered wood|wood products]], [[Pulp (paper)|pulp paper products]], [[chemicals]], [[Ceramic|ceramic products]], [[plastic]] and [[Rubber technology|rubber products]], [[Electrical equipment|electrical]] and [[Consumer electronics|electronic products]], [[base metal]]s: [[iron]] and [[steel]], [[information technology]], [[Automotive industry|automobile manufacturing]], and other manufacturing (2015)<ref name=\"Product Report NBS\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng/pages/download/312 | title=Nigerian Gross Domestic Product Report Q2 2015 | publisher=National Bureau of Statistics | access-date=22 September 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915131636/http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng/pages/download/312 | archivedate=15 September 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|exports         = {{increase}} $46.68 billion (2017)<ref name=\"OPEC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.opec.org/opec_web/en/about_us/167.htm |title=Nigeria facts and figures|publisher=[[OPEC]] |website=www.opec.org |access-date=30 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"OEC\">{{cite web|url=https://atlas.media.mit.edu/en/profile/country/nga/#Exports |title=Nigeria |publisher=The Observatory of Economic Complexity |access-date=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n|export-goods    = [[petroleum]] and [[petroleum products]], [[chemical]]s, [[vehicle]]s, [[aircraft]] parts, [[Watercraft|vessel]]s, [[vegetable]] products, [[processed food]], [[beverages]], [[spirit]]s and [[vinegar]], [[cashew nuts]], processed [[leather]], [[Cocoa bean|cocoa]], [[tobacco]], [[aluminum alloy]]s <br /> (2015)<ref name=\"Foreign Trade - NBS\" />\n|export-partners = {{plainlist|\n*{{flag|India}} 18%\n*{{flag|United States}} 14%\n*{{flag|Spain}} 9.7%\n*{{flag|France}} 6.0%\n*{{flag|Netherlands}} 4.9%\n*{{flag|Germany}} 3.6%\n*(2017)<ref name=\"OEC\" />}}\n|imports         = {{decreasePositive}} $34.2 billion (2017)<ref name=\"OEC\"/>\n|import-goods    = [[industry]] supplies, [[machinery]], [[Home appliance|appliance]]s, [[vehicle]]s, [[aircraft]] parts, chemicals, [[base metal]]s <br /> (2015)<ref name=\"Foreign Trade - NBS\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng/pages/download/311 | title=Foreign Trade Statistics | publisher=National Bureau of Statistics | date=2015 | accessdate=22 September 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915123934/http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng/pages/download/311 | archivedate=15 September 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|import-partners = {{plainlist|\n*{{flag|China}} 28%\n*{{flag|Belgium}} {{flag|Luxembourg}} 8.9%\n*{{flag|Netherlands}} 8.3%\n*{{flag| South Korea}} 6.4%\n*{{flag|United States}} 6.0%\n*{{flag|India}} 4.6%\n*(2017)<ref name=\"OEC\" />}}\n|current account = {{increase}} $10.38 billion (2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIA World Fact Book - Nigeria\"/>\n|FDI             = {{plainlist|\n*{{increase}} $116.9 billion (31 December 2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIA World Fact Book - Nigeria\"/>\n*{{increase}} Abroad: $16.93 billion (31 December 2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIA World Fact Book - Nigeria\"/>}}\n|gross external debt = {{increaseNegative}} $40.96 billion (31 December 2017 est.)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/fields/246.html#NI|title=DEBT - EXTERNAL |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] |website=CIA.gov |access-date=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n|debt            = {{increaseNegative}} 21.8% of GDP (2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIA World Fact Book - Nigeria\"/>\n|revenue         = $54.48 billion\n|expenses        = $31.61 billion (2012 est.)\n|balance         = $5.2 billion; 1% of GDP (2014)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://m.news24.com/Nigeria/Business/News/Nigerias-budget-deficit-now-1-after-rebasing-20140527 | title=Nigeria's budget deficit now 1% after rebasing | publisher=News 24 | date=27 May 2014 | access-date=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n|aid             = \n|credit          = {{plainlist|\n*[[Standard & Poor's]]:<ref>{{cite web |title= Sovereigns rating list |publisher=Standard & Poor's |url=http://www.standardandpoors.com/ratings/sovereigns/ratings-list/en/eu/?subSectorCode=39 |accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n*B+ (Domestic)\n*B+ (Foreign)\n*B+ (T&C Assessment)\n*Outlook: Stable<ref name=guardian>{{cite news |title=How Fitch, Moody's and S&P rate each country's credit rating |date=15 April 2011 |first1=Simon |last1=Rogers |first2=Ami |last2=Sedghi |work=The Guardian |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2010/apr/30/credit-ratings-country-fitch-moodys-standard |accessdate=31 May 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\n*[[Fitch Group|Fitch]]:<ref name=guardian/>\n*BB-\n*Outlook: Stable}}\n|reserves        = {{increase}} $38.77 billion (31 December 2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIA World Fact Book - Nigeria\"/>\n|cianame         = ni\n|spelling        = \n}}\n\nThe '''economy of Nigeria''' is a middle-income, [[mixed economy]] and [[emerging market]], with expanding manufacturing, financial, service, communications, technology and entertainment sectors. It is ranked as the [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|27th-largest economy in the world in terms of nominal GDP]], and the [[List of countries by GDP (PPP)|22nd-largest in terms of purchasing power parity]]. [[Nigeria]] has the largest economy in Africa; its re-emergent manufacturing sector became the largest on the continent in 2013, and it produces a large proportion of goods and services for the [[West Africa]]n subcontinent.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kpmg.com/Africa/en/IssuesAndInsights/Articles-Publications/General-Industries-Publications/Documents/Manufacturing%20sector%20report%202015.pdf |title=Manufacturing Sector Report, 2015: Manufacturing in Africa |year=2015 |publisher=[[KPMG]] |access-date=18 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927185014/http://www.kpmg.com/Africa/en/IssuesAndInsights/Articles-Publications/General-Industries-Publications/Documents/Manufacturing%20sector%20report%202015.pdf |archive-date=27 September 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In addition, the [[debt-to-GDP ratio]] is 16.075 percent as of 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ceicdata.com/en/indicator/nigeria/government-debt--of-nominal-gdp |title=UPDATE Nigeria Government Debt: % of GDP |access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNigerian GDP at purchasing power parity (PPP) has almost tripled from $170 billion in 2000 to $451 billion in 2012, although estimates of the size of the [[informal sector]] (which is not included in official figures) put the actual numbers closer to $630 billion. Correspondingly, the GDP per capita doubled from $1400 per person in 2000 to an estimated $2,800 per person in 2012 (again, with the inclusion of the informal sector, it is estimated that GDP per capita hovers around $3,900 per person). (Population increased from 120 million in 2000 to 160 million in 2010). These figures were to be revised upwards by as much as 80% when metrics were to be recalculated subsequent to the rebasing of its economy in April 2014.{{Update inline|date=April 2017}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?tbm=nws&q=nigeria+rebasing+gdp|title=nigeria rebasing gdp - Google Search|publisher=|access-date=11 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlthough oil revenues contribute 2/3 of state revenues,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/77886786-0fc9-11e7-b030-768954394623|title=Subscribe to read|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2017-06-02}}</ref> oil only contributes about 9% to the GDP. Nigeria produces only about 2.7% of the world's oil supply (in comparison, [[Saudi Arabia]] produces 12.9%, [[Russia]] produces 12.7% and the [[United States]] produces 8.6%).<ref>[[Petroleum#Production|- World Petroleum Production]]</ref> Although the petroleum sector is important, as government revenues still heavily rely on this sector, it remains a small part of the country's overall economy.\n\nThe largely subsistence agricultural sector has not kept up with rapid population growth, and Nigeria, once a large net exporter of food, now{{When|date=April 2017}} imports some of its food products, though mechanization has led to a resurgence in manufacturing and exporting of food products, and the move towards food sufficiency. In 2006, Nigeria came to an agreement with the [[Paris Club]] to buy back the bulk of its debts owed from them for a cash payment of roughly US$12 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cgdev.org/content/publications/detail/3223/|title=Resolving Nigeria's Debt Through a Discounted Buyback|work=Center For Global Development|access-date=11 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a [[Citigroup]] report published in February 2011, Nigeria will have the highest average GDP growth in the world between 2010 and 2050. Nigeria is one of two countries from Africa among 11 [[3G (countries)|Global Growth Generators]] countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/willem-buiter-3g-countries-2011-2?slop=1 |title=FORGET THE BRICs: Citi's Willem Buiter Presents The 11 \"3G\" Countries That Will Win The Future |publisher=businessinsider.com |date=22 February 2011 |access-date=31 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nIn 2014, Nigeria changed its economic analysis to account for rapidly growing contributors to its GDP, such as telecommunications, banking, and its film industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21600685-nigerias-suddenly-supersized-economy-indeed-wonder-so-are-its-still-huge|title=Africa\u2019s new Number One|author=|date=|work=Economist.com|access-date=9 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Nigeria reached an agreement with the Paris Club of lending nations to eliminate all of its bilateral external debt. Under the agreement, the lenders will forgive most of the debt, and Nigeria will pay off the remainder with a portion of its energy revenues.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Adenikinju|first=Adeola|date=2003-01-01|title=Efficiency of the Energy Sector and its Impact on the Competitiveness of the Nigerian Economy|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/237734443_Efficiency_of_the_Energy_Sector_and_its_Impact_on_the_Competitiveness_of_the_Nigerian_Economy}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cgdev.org/topics/nigerian-debt-relief|title=Nigerian Debt Relief|website=Center For Global Development|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Moreover, human capital is underdeveloped\u2014Nigeria ranked 151 out of countries in the United Nations Development Index in 2004\u2014and non-energy-related infrastructure is inadequate.\n\nFrom 2003 to 2007, Nigeria attempted to implement an economic reform program called the National Economic Empowerment Development Strategy (NEEDS). The purpose of the NEEDS was to raise the country's [[standard of living]] through a variety of reforms, including macroeconomic stability, [[deregulation]], [[liberalization]], [[privatization]], transparency, and accountability.\n\nThe NEEDS addressed basic deficiencies, such as the lack of freshwater for household use and irrigation, unreliable power supplies, decaying infrastructure, impediments to private enterprise, and corruption. NEEDS was intended to create 7 million new jobs, diversify the economy, boost non-energy exports, increase industrial capacity utilization, and improve agricultural productivity. A related initiative on the state level is the State Economic Empowerment Development Strategy (SEEDS).\n\nA longer-term economic development program is the United Nations (UN)-sponsored National Millennium Goals for Nigeria. Under the program, which covers the years from 2000 to 2015, Nigeria is committed to achieving a wide range of ambitious objectives involving poverty reduction, education, gender equality, health, the environment, and international development cooperation. In an update released in 2004, the UN found that Nigeria was making progress toward achieving several goals but was falling short on others.\n\nSpecifically, Nigeria had advanced efforts to provide universal primary education, protect the environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.christenseninstitute.org/blog/why-innovation-must-be-the-new-development-strategy/|title=Why innovation must be the new development strategy|date=2017-01-19|website=Christensen Institute|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yourcommonwealth.org/uncategorized/nigerias-challenge-universal-primary-education/|title=\u201cNigeria\u2019s challenge \u2013 universal primary education\u201d {{!}} YourCommonwealth|website=www.yourcommonwealth.org|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\nA prerequisite for achieving many of these worthwhile objectives is curtailing endemic corruption, which stymies development and taints Nigeria's business environment. President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]]'s campaign against corruption, which includes the arrest of officials accused of misdeeds and recovering stolen funds, has won praise from the [[World Bank]]. In September 2005, Nigeria, with the assistance of the World Bank, began to recover US$458 million of illicit funds that had been deposited in Swiss banks by the late military dictator Sani Abacha, who ruled Nigeria from 1993 to 1998. However, while broad-based progress has been slow, these efforts have begun to become evident in international surveys of corruption. Nigeria's ranking has consistently improved since 2001 ranking 147 out of 180 countries in [[Transparency International]]'s 2007 [[Corruption Perceptions Index]].\n\nThe Nigerian economy suffers from an ongoing [[Nigerian energy supply crisis|supply crisis in the power sector]]. Despite a rapidly growing economy, some of the world's [[List of countries by proven oil reserves|largest deposits of coal, oil and gas]] and the country's status as Africa's largest oil producer, power supply difficulties are frequently experienced by residents.\n\n== Economic history ==\n{{Further|Economic history of Nigeria}}\nThis is a chart of trend of gross domestic product of Nigeria at market prices estimated<ref>[http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2006/01/data/dbcselm.cfm?G=2001 estimated]</ref> by the [[International Monetary Fund]] with figures in USD billions. Figures before 2000 are backwards projections from the 2000\u20132012 numbers, based on historical growth rates, and should be replaced when data becomes available. The figure for 2014 is derived from a rebasing of economical activity earlier in the year.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year || Gross domestic product,<br /> (PPP, in billions) || US dollar exchange || Inflation index<br/>(2000=100) || Per capita income<br/> (as % of USA)\n|-\n| 1980 || *58 || 1 Naira || 1.30 || 7%\n|-\n| 1985 || *82 || 3 Naira || 3.20 || 5%\n|-\n| 1990 || *118 || 9 Naira || 8.10 || 2.5%\n|-\n| 1995 || *155 || 50 Naira || 56 || 3%\n|-\n| 2000 || 170 || 100 Naira || 100 || 3.5%\n|-\n| 2005 || 291 || 130 Naira || 207 || 4%\n|-\n| 2010 || 392 || 150 Naira || 108 || 5%\n|-\n| 2012 || 451 || 158 Naira || 121 || 7%\n|-\n| 2014 || 972    || 180 Naira  || 10 || 11%\n|-\n| 2015 || 1,089 || 220 Naira  || 10 || 10%\n|-\n| 2016 || 1,093 || 280 Naira  || 17 || 10%\n|-\n| 2017 || 1,125 || 360 Naira  ||  5 (est)  ||   10%\n|}\n\nNOTES:\n\nThe US dollar exchange rate is an estimated average of the official rate throughout a year, and does not reflect the parallel market rate at which the general population accesses foreign exchange. This rate ranged from a high of 520 in March 2017 to a low of 350 in August 2017, due to a scarcity of forex (oil earnings had dropped by half), and to speculative activity as alleged by the Central Bank. All the while the official rate was pegged at 360.\n\nPer capita income (as % of USA) is calculated using data from estimates in the PPP link above, and from census estimates, based on growth rates between census periods. For instance 2017 GDPs were 1,125 Billion (Nigeria) vs. 19,417 Billion (USA) and populations were estimated at 320 million vs 190 million. The ratio is therefore (1125/19417) / (190/320), which roughly comes to 0.0975. These are estimates and are intended to get a feel for the relative wealth and standard of living, as well as the market potential of its middle class.\n\nThis is a chart of trend of the global ranking of the Nigerian economy, in comparison with other countries of the world, derived from the historical [[List of countries by GDP (PPP)]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year    || 2005 || 2006 || 2007 || 2008 || 2009 || 2010 || 2011 || 2012 || 2013 || 2014 || 2015 || 2016 || 2017 (est.)\n|-\n| Ranking || 52   ||  47  || 38   ||  37  ||  34  || 31   ||  31  ||  30 || 23 || 20 || 21 || 22 || 23\n|}\n\nThis chart shows the variance in the parallel exchange rate at which the Dollar can be obtained with Naira in Lagos, with \"Best\" being cheaper for a Nigerian (i.e. stronger Naira).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abokifx.com/|title=Your daily Naira exchange rate|website=www.abokifx.com|access-date=2017-08-23}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nairametrics.com/naira-dollar-parallel-market-exchange-rate-daily/|title=Daily Parallel Market Exchange Rate|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nairametrics.com|access-date=2017-08-23}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year    || 2015 || 2016 || 2017 \n|-\n| Best || 195 || 345 || 350\n|-\n| Worst || 237 || 490 || 520\n|}\n\nFor purchasing power parity comparisons, the US dollar is exchanged at 1 USD to 314.27 [[Nigerian naira|Nigerian Naira]] (as of 2017).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xe.com/currencyconverter/convert/?Amount=1&From=USD&To=NGN|title=XE: Convert USD/NGN. United States Dollar to Nigeria Naira|website=www.xe.com|access-date=2017-06-02}}</ref>\n\nCurrent GDP per capita of Nigeria expanded 132% in the sixties reaching a peak growth of 283% in the seventies. But this proved unsustainable and it consequently shrank by 66% in the Eighties. In the Nineties, diversification initiatives finally took effect and decadal growth was restored to 10%. Although GDP on a PPP basis did not increase until the 2000's.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://factfish.com/statistic-country/nigeria/gross%20domestic%20product%20per%20capita,%20constant%202005%20us%20$|title=factfish Gross domestic product per capita, constant 2005 US $ for Nigeria|website=factfish.com|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the GDP was composed of the following sectors: agriculture: 40%; services: 30%; manufacturing: 15%; oil: 14%.<ref name=\"National Bureau of Statistics\">{{cite web|url= http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng |title= News 2012|publisher=Nigerian National Bureau of Statistics|access-date=26 March 2012}}</ref> By 2015, the GDP was composed of the following sectors: agriculture: 18%; services: 55%; manufacturing: 16%;  oil: 8% <ref name=\"Product Report NBS\" />\n\nIn 2005 Nigeria's inflation rate was an estimated 15.6%. Nigeria's goal under the National Economic Empowerment Development Strategy (NEEDS) program is to reduce inflation to the single digits. By 2015, Nigeria's inflation stood at 9%. In 2005, the federal government had expenditures of US$13.54 billion but revenues of only US$12.86 billion, resulting in a budget deficit of 5%. By 2012, expenditures stood at $31.61 billion, while revenues was $54.48 billion.\n\n== Economic sectors ==\n\n===Agriculture===\n{{Further|Agriculture in Nigeria}}\n\n[[File:Nigerian farmers.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Nigerian farmers in the [[Middle Belt]] (2006). 30% of Nigerians are employed in agriculture.<ref name=\"same name\">Olomola Ade S. (2007) \u201cStrategies for Managing the Opportunities and Challenges of the Current Agricultural Commodity Booms in SSA\u201d in Seminar Papers on Managing Commodity Booms in Sub-Saharan Africa: A Publication of the AERC Senior Policy Seminar IX. African Economic Research Consortium (AERC), Nairobi, Kenya</ref>]]\nNigeria [[List of countries by agricultural output|ranks sixth]] worldwide and first in Africa in farm output. The sector accounts for about 18% of GDP and almost one-third of employment. Nigeria has 19 million head of cattle, the largest in Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201405160659.html|title=Nigeria to Increase Beef Consumption to 1.3 Million Tonnes By 2050 - Adesina|author=|date=16 May 2014|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2017|via=AllAfrica}}</ref> Though Nigeria is no longer a major exporter, due to local consumer boom, it is still a major producer of many agricultural products, including: cocoa, groundnuts (peanuts), rubber, and palm oil. [[Cocoa bean|Cocoa]] production, mostly from obsolete varieties and overage trees has increased from around 180,000 tons annually to 350,000 tons.\n\nMajor agricultural products include [[Cassava production in Nigeria|cassava]] (tapioca), corn, cocoa, millet, palm oil, peanuts, rice, rubber, sorghum, and yams. In 2003, livestock production, in order of metric tonnage, featured eggs, milk, beef and veal, poultry, and pork, respectively. In the same year, the total fishing catch was 505.8 metric tons. Roundwood removals totaled slightly less than 70 million cubic meters, and sawnwood production was estimated at 2 million cubic meters. The agricultural sector suffers from extremely low productivity, reflecting reliance on antiquated methods. Agriculture has failed to keep pace with Nigeria's rapid population growth, so that the country, which once exported food, now imports a significant amount of food to sustain itself. However, efforts are being made towards making the country food sufficient again.\n\n===Oil===\n{{Further|Petroleum industry in Nigeria}}\nNigeria's proven [[oil reserves]] are estimated to be {{convert|35|Goilbbl|m3}}; natural gas reserves are well over {{convert|100|Tcuft|km3}}. Nigeria is a member of the [[Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries]] (OPEC). The types of [[crude oil]] exported by Nigeria are [[Bonny light oil]], [[Forcados crude oil]], [[Qua Ibo crude oil]] and [[Brass River crude oil]]. Poor corporate relations with indigenous communities, vandalism of oil infrastructure, severe ecological damage, and personal security problems throughout the [[Niger Delta]] oil-producing region continue to plague Nigeria's oil sector.\n\nEfforts are underway{{When|date=April 2017}} to reverse these troubles. A new entity, the [[Niger Delta Development Commission]] (NDDC), has been created to help catalyze economic and social development in the region. The U.S. remains Nigeria's largest buyer of crude oil, accounting for 40% of the country's total oil exports; Nigeria provides about 10% of overall U.S. oil imports and ranks as the fifth-largest source for U.S. imported oil.\n\nThe United Kingdom is Nigeria's largest trading partner followed by the United States. Although the trade balance overwhelmingly favors Nigeria, thanks to oil exports, a large portion of U.S. exports to Nigeria is believed to enter the country outside of the Nigerian government's official statistics, due to importers seeking to avoid Nigeria's tariffs. To counter smuggling and under-invoicing by importers, in May 2001, the Nigerian government instituted a full inspection program for all imports, and enforcement has been sustained.\n\nOn the whole, Nigerian high tariffs and non-tariff barriers are gradually being reduced,{{When|date=April 2017}} but much progress remains to be made.{{According to whom|date=April 2017}} The government also has been encouraging the expansion of foreign investment, although the country's investment climate remains daunting to all but the most determined.{{According to whom|date=April 2017}} The stock of U.S. investment is nearly $7 billion, mostly in the energy sector. [[Exxon Mobil]] and [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]] are the two largest U.S. corporations in offshore oil and gas production. Significant exports of liquefied natural gas started in late 1999 and are slated to expand as Nigeria seeks to eliminate gas flaring by 2008.\n\nThe pump price of P.M.S. currently{{When|date=April 2017}} stands at around \u20a6145 at fueling stations across Nigeria. An initial increase in the price of petrol (Premium Motor Spirit) from around \u20a665 to \u20a6140 triggered by the removal of fuel subsidies on January 1, 2012, triggered a total strike and massive protests across the country. Then President [[Goodluck Ebele Jonathan]] later reached an agreement with the [[Nigerian Labour Congress]] and reduced the pump price to 97 naira. The pump price was further reduced by 10 naira to 87 naira in the run-up to the 2015 general elections. However, after the elections of [[Muhammadu Buhari]], the fuel subsidies was removed again, and the pump price increased again, despite the fall in oil price.\n \nSince the fall in oil prices in 2015 and 2016, the government exchange rate policy has limited devaluation of the naira due to inflation concerns by the President Muhammadu Buhari.<ref name=\"Can you spare a dollar\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21695065-how-make-hard-currency-shortage-worse-can-you-spare-dollar|title=Can you spare a dollar?|newspaper=The Economist|issn=0013-0613|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pulse.ng/local/buhari-why-president-should-devalue-naira-chuba-ezekwesili-video-id4824955.html|title=Buhari: Why President should devalue naira \u2013 Chuba Ezekwesili [VIDEO]|last=Sotubo|first='Jola|website=pulse.ng|access-date=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Services===\nNigeria [[List of countries by GDP sector composition|ranks 27th]] worldwide and first in Africa in services' output.\n\nSince undergoing severe distress in the mid-1990s, Nigeria's banking sector has witnessed significant growth over the last few years{{When|date=April 2017}} as new banks enter the financial market.\n\nPrivate sector-led economic growth remains stymied by the high cost of doing business in Nigeria, including the need to duplicate essential infrastructure, the lack of effective due process, and nontransparent economic decision making, especially in government contracting. While corrupt practices are endemic, they are generally less flagrant than during military rule, and there are signs of improvement. Meanwhile, since 1999 the Nigerian Stock Exchange has enjoyed strong performance, although equity as a means to foster corporate growth is being more utilized by Nigeria's private sector.{{According to whom|date=April 2017}}\n\n====Transport====\n{{main|Transport in Nigeria}}\n\n[[File:Lagos Life goes on.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Minibuses in Lagos]]\nNigeria's publicly owned transportation infrastructure is a major constraint to economic development. Principal ports are at [[Lagos]] ([[Apapa]] and [[Tin Can Island]]), [[Port Harcourt]] (Onne), and [[Calabar]].\n\nExtensive road repairs and new construction activities are gradually being implemented as state governments, in particular, spend their portions of enhanced government revenue allocations.\n\nFive of Nigeria's airports (Lagos, [[Kano]], [[Port Harcourt]], [[Enugu]] and [[Abuja]]) currently fly to international destinations. The [[Nigerian Airforce]] began a new airline called United Nigeria, with a [[Boeing 737-500]] in 2013. There are several domestic private Nigerian carriers, and air service among Nigeria's cities is generally dependable.\n\n==== Tourism ====\n{{Further|Tourism in Nigeria}}\n\n=== Mining ===\n{{Further|Mining industry of Nigeria}}\n\n=== Energy ===\n{{Further|Energy in Nigeria}}\n\n==== Data ====\n\n'''Electricity \u2013 production:'''\n18.89 billion kWh (2009)\n\n'''Electricity \u2013 production by source:'''\n<br />''fossil fuel:''\n61.69%\n<br />''hydro:''\n38.31%\n<br />''nuclear:''\n0%\n<br />''other:''\n<.1% (1998)\n\n'''Electricity - consumption:'''\n17.66 billion kWh (2009)\n\n'''Electricity - exports:'''\n40 million kWh (2003)\n\n'''Electricity - imports:'''\n0 kWh (1998)\n\n'''Oil - production:''' \n{{convert|2.35|Moilbbl/d}} (July 2006 est.)\n\n'''Oil - consumption:'''\n{{convert|310000|oilbbl/d|abbr=on}} (2003 est.)\n\n===Overseas remittances===\nA major source of foreign exchange earnings for Nigeria are [[remittances]] sent home by Nigerians living abroad.<ref name=\"tribune.com.ng\">[http://www.tribune.com.ng/business/tribune-business/item/15469-remittances-from-diaspora-nigerians-as-lubricant-for-the-economy/15469-remittances-from-diaspora-nigerians-as-lubricant-for-the-economy \"Remittances from diaspora Nigerians as lubricant for the economy\",] [[Nigerian Tribune]]<span wfd-id=\"1034\">, 8 September 2014.</span> {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317150032/http://www.tribune.com.ng/business/tribune-business/item/15469-remittances-from-diaspora-nigerians-as-lubricant-for-the-economy/15469-remittances-from-diaspora-nigerians-as-lubricant-for-the-economy |date=17 March 2015 }}</ref> In 2014, 17.5 million Nigerians lived in foreign countries, with the UK and the USA having more than 2 million Nigerians each.<ref name=\"tribune.com.ng\"/>\n\nAccording to the [[International Organization for Migration]], Nigeria witnessed a dramatic increase in [[remittances]] sent home from overseas Nigerians, going from USD $2.3 billion in 2004 to $17.9 billion in 2007, representing 6.7% of GDP. The United States accounts for the largest portion of official remittances, followed by the United Kingdom, Italy, Canada, Spain and France. On the African continent, Egypt, Equatorial Guinea, Chad, Libya and South Africa are important source countries of remittance flows to Nigeria, while China is the biggest remittance-sending country in Asia.\n\n==Labour force==\nIn 2015, Nigeria had a labour force of 74 million. In 2003, the unemployment rate was 10.8% overall; by 2015, unemployment stood at 6.4%.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.punchng.com/business/business-economy/only-4-67-million-nigerians-are-unemployed-nbs/ | title=Only 4.67 million Nigerians are unemployed \u2014NBS | publisher=The Punch Newspaper | date=15 May 2015 | access-date=17 May 2015 | author=Onuba, Ifeanyi | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526214618/http://www.punchng.com/business/business-economy/only-4-67-million-nigerians-are-unemployed-nbs/ | archivedate=26 May 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSince 1999, the Nigerian Labor Congress (NLC) a union umbrella organization, has called six general strikes to protest domestic fuel price increases. However, in March 2005 the government introduced legislation ending the NLC's monopoly over union organizing. In December 2005, the NLC was lobbying for an increase in the minimum wage for federal workers. The existing minimum wage, which was introduced six years earlier but has not been adjusted since, has been whittled away by inflation to only US$42.80 per month.\n\nAccording to the [[International Organization for Migration]], the number of [[immigrants]] residing in Nigeria has more than doubled in recent decades \u2013 from 477,135 in 1991 to 971,450 in 2005. The majority of immigrants in Nigeria (74%) are from neighbouring [[Economic Community of West African States]] (ECOWAS), and that this number has increased considerably over the last decade, from 63% in 2001 to 97% in 2005.\n\n===Human capital===\n{{Further|Education in Nigeria}}\nThe [[Human Development Index]] (HDI) shows in 2012 that Nigeria is ranked 156 with the value of 0.459 among 187 countries. As of 2015, Nigeria's HDI is ranked 152nd at 0.514. The comparative value for Sub-Saharan Africa is 0.475, 0.910 for the US,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hdrstats.undp.org/en/countries/profiles/USA.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119004452/http://hdrstats.undp.org/en/countries/profiles/USA.html |archivedate=19 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and 0.694 for the world average.\n\nThe value for the education index is 0.457, compared to the average in the US of 0.939. The expected years of schooling in Nigeria is 9.0 (16.00 in the US), while the mean years of schooling for adults over 25 years is 5.2 years (12.4 years in the US). Additionally, Nigeria is also facing a relatively high inequality, worsening the problem regarding the formation of human capital. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/jan/21/world-26-richest-people-own-as-much-as-poorest-50-per-cent-oxfam-report|title=World's 26 richest people own as much as poorest 50%, says Oxfam|last=Elliott|first=Larry|date=2019-01-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-03|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldpoverty.io/|title=World Poverty Clock|website=worldpoverty.io|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n== Government policy ==\n\n=== Inflation ===\n{{Original research|section|date=April 2017}}In the light of highly expansionary public sector fiscal policies in 2001, the government sought ways to head off higher inflation, leading to the implementation of stronger monetary policies by the [[Central Bank of Nigeria]] (CBN) and underspending of budgeted amounts. As a result of the CBN's efforts, the official exchange rate for the Naira had stabilized at about 112 Naira to the dollar. The combination of CBN's efforts to prop up the value of the Naira and excess liquidity resulting from government spending led the currency to be discounted by around 20% on the parallel (non-official) market.\n\nA key condition of the Stand-by Arrangement has been closure of the gap between the official and parallel market exchange rates. The [[Inter Bank Foreign Exchange Market]] (IFEM) is closely tied to the official rate. Under IFEM, banks, oil companies, and the CBN can buy or sell their foreign exchange at government-influenced rates. Much of the informal economy, however, can only access foreign exchange through the parallel market. Companies can hold domiciliary accounts in private banks, and account holders have unfettered use of the funds.\n\nExpanded government spending also has led to upward pressure on consumer prices. Inflation which had almost disappeared in April 2000 reached 14.5% by the end of the year and 18.7% in August 2001. In 2000, high oil prices resulted in government revenue of over $16 billion, about double the 1999 level. State and local governments demanded access to this \"windfall\" revenue, creating a tug-of-war between the federal government, which sought to control spending, and state governments desiring augmented budgets, preventing the government from making provision for periods of lower oil prices.\n\nIn 2016, the black market exchange rate of the Naira was about 60% above the official rate. The central bank releases about $200 million each week at the official exchange rate. However, some companies cite that budgets now include a 30% \u201cpremium\u201d to be paid to central bank officials to get dollars.<ref name=\"Can you spare a dollar\"/>\n\n===Gradual reform===\n{{Original research|section|date=April 2017}}The Obasanjo government supported \"private-sector\" led, \"market oriented\" [[economic growth]] and began extensive economic reform efforts. Although the government's anti-corruption campaign was left wanting, progress in injecting transparency and accountability into economic decision-making was notable. The dual exchange rate mechanism formally abolished in the 1999 budget remains in place in actuality.\n\nDuring 2000 the government's privatization program showed signs of life and real promise with successful turnover to the private sector of state-owned banks, fuel distribution companies, and cement plants. However, the privatization process has slowed somewhat as the government confronts key parastatals such as the state telephone company [[NITEL]] and Nigerian Airways. The successful auction of GSM telecommunications licenses in January 2001 has encouraged investment in this vital sector.\n\nAlthough the government has been stymied so far in its desire to deregulate downstream petroleum prices, state refineries, almost paralyzed in 2000, are producing at much higher capacities. By August 2001, gasoline lines disappeared throughout much of the country. The government still intends to pursue deregulation despite significant internal opposition, particularly from the [[Nigeria Labour Congress]]. To meet market demand the government incurs large losses importing gasoline to sell at subsidized prices.\n\n==Foreign economic relations==\nNigeria's foreign economic relations revolve around its role in supplying the world economy with oil and natural gas, even as the country seeks to diversify its exports, harmonize tariffs in line with a potential [[customs union]] sought by the [[Economic Community of West African States]] (ECOWAS), and encourage inflows of foreign portfolio and direct investment. In October 2005, Nigeria implemented the ECOWAS [[common external tariff]], which reduced the number of tariff bands.\n\nPrior to this revision, tariffs constituted Nigeria's second largest source of revenue after oil exports. In 2005 Nigeria achieved a major breakthrough when it reached an agreement with the Paris Club to eliminate its bilateral debt through a combination of write-downs and buybacks. Nigeria joined the [[Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries]] in July 1971 and the [[World Trade Organization]] in January 1995.\n\n===External trade===\n[[Image:2006Nigeria exports.PNG|thumb|upright=2|Nigeria's exports in 2006.]]\n[[File:Nigeria Export Treemap (2011).png|upright=2|thumb|A proportional representation of Nigeria's exports.]]\nIn 2017, Nigeria imported about US$34.2 billion of goods. In 2017 the leading sources of imports were China (28%), the Belgium-Luxembourg (8.9%), the Netherlands (8.3%), South Korea (6.4%), the United States (6.0%) and the Republic of India (4.6%).<ref name=\"OEC\"/> Principal imports were manufactured goods, machinery and transport equipment, chemicals, and food and live animals.\n\nIn 2017, Nigeria exported about US$46.68 billion of goods.<ref name=\"OPEC\"/> In 2017, the leading destinations for exports were India (18%), the United States (14%), Spain (9.7%), France (6.0%) and the Netherlands (4.9%).<ref name=\"OEC\"/> In 2017 oil accounted for 83% of merchandise exports.<ref name=\"OPEC\"/> Natural rubber and cocoa are the country\u2019s major agricultural exports.<ref name=\"CIA World Fact Book - Nigeria\"/>\n\nIn 2005, Nigeria posted a US$26 billion trade surplus, corresponding to almost 20% of gross domestic product. In 2005, Nigeria achieved a positive current account balance of US$9.6 billion. The Nigerian currency is the [[naira]] (NGN). As of June 2006, the [[exchange rate]] was about US$1=NGN128.4. As of June 2019, it stands at US$1 =NGN357. In recent years, Nigeria has expanded its trade relations with other developing countries such as India. Nigeria is the largest African crude oil supplier to India \u2014 it annually exports {{convert|400000|oilbbl/d|m3/d}} to India valued at US$10 billion annually.\n\nIndia is the largest purchaser of Nigeria's oil which fulfills 20% to 25% of India's domestic oil demand. Indian oil companies are also involved in oil drilling operations in Nigeria and have plans to set up refineries there.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/india-now-nigerias-biggest-crude-oil-buyer/article4917091.ece?homepage=true | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=India now Nigeria's biggest crude oil buyer | date=15 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe trade volume between Nigeria and the United Kingdom rose by 35% from [[USD]]6.3 billion in 2010 to [[USD]]8.5 billion in 2011.<ref>{{Citation\n| url = http://allafrica.com/stories/201209261080.html\n| title= Nigeria, UK Trade Hits U.S.$9 Billion in 2011\n| year =  2012\n| publisher = [[AllAfrica.com]]\n| publication-place = [[Africa]]\n| accessdate = 27 September 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n===External debt===\nIn 2012, Nigeria's external debt was an estimated $5.9 billion and N5.6 trillion domestic - putting total debt at $44 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/nigeria-s-domestic-external-debts-now-44bn/113910/|title=Nigeria\u2019s Domestic, External Debts Now $44bn, Articles - THISDAY LIVE|publisher=|accessdate=11 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613031521/http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/nigeria-s-domestic-external-debts-now-44bn/113910/|archivedate=13 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006, Nigeria became the first African country to fully pay off its debt owed to the [[Paris Club]]. This was structured as a debt writeoff of approximately $18 billion and a cash payment of approximately $12 billion.\n\n===Foreign investment===\nIn 2012, Nigeria received a net inflow of US$85.73 billion of [[foreign direct investment]] (FDI), much of which came from Nigerians in the diaspora. Most FDI is directed toward the energy and banking sectors. Any public designed to encourage inflow of foreign capital is capable of generating employment opportunities within the domestic economy. The Nigerian Enterprises Promotion (NEP) Decree of 1972 (revised in 1977) was intended to reduce foreign investment in the Nigerian economy.\n\nThe stock [[market capitalisation]] of listed companies in Nigeria was valued at $97.75 billion on 15 February 2008 by the [[Nigerian Stock Exchange]].\n\n===Swiss Banks to return Abacha Funds===\nThe Swiss foreign ministry says it has done all it can to ensure that funds stolen by the late Nigerian dictator [[Sani Abacha]] were used properly in his homeland. The authorities were responding to allegations that $200 million (SFr240 million) of $700 million handed back by the [[Swiss Banks]] to Nigeria had been misappropriated.\n\n==Data==\n'''Household income or consumption by percentage share:'''\n<br />''lowest 10%:''\n2.6%\n<br />''highest 10%:''\n35.8% (1996\u201397)\n\n'''Industries:'''\n[[crude oil]], [[coal]], [[tin]], [[columbite]], [[palm oil]], [[peanut]]s, [[cotton]], [[rubber]], wood, hides and skins, textiles, [[cement]] and other construction materials, food products, footwear, chemicals, fertilizer, printing, [[ceramic]]s, [[steel]], small commercial [[ship]] [[construction]] and repair\n\n'''Industrial production growth rate:'''\n4.7% (2010 est.)\n\n'''Agriculture \u2013 products:'''\n[[Cocoa bean|cocoa]], [[peanut]]s, [[palm oil]], [[maize]], [[rice]], [[sorghum]], [[millet]], [[cassava]] ([[tapioca]]), [[yam (vegetable)|yams]], [[rubber]]; [[cattle]], [[domestic sheep|sheep]], [[goat]]s, [[domestic pig|pig]]s; [[timber]]; [[fish]]\n\n'''Exchange rates:'''\nNaira (NGN) per US$1 \u2013 358 (2019), 157.3 (2012) 149.5 (2009), 120 (2006), 128 (2005), 132.89 (2004), 129.22 (2003), 120.58 (2002), 111.23 (2001)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Poverty in Nigeria]]\n* [[Steel industry in Nigeria]]\n* [[United Nations Economic Commission for Africa]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{loc}}\n54. [https://careerwatch.ng/fg-jobs/ Nigerian Federal government Recruitment] careerwatch.ng February 23 2020\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/WDSP/IB/2013/05/14/000333037_20130514101211/Rendered/PDF/776840WP0Niger0Box0342041B00PUBLIC0.pdf The World Bank Economic Report on Nigeria, May 2013]\n\n==External links==\n*{{curlie|Regional/Africa/Nigeria/Business_and_Economy/Economic_Development}}\n{{External links|date=April 2017}}\n*[http://wits.worldbank.org/CountryProfile/Country/NGA/Year/2012/Summary World Bank Summary Trade Statistics Nigeria]\n*[http://www.trademap.org/open_access/Index.aspx?proceed=true&reporter=566 Nigeria latest trade data on ITC Trade Map]\n*Tariffs applied by Nigeria as provided by ITC's [http://www.macmap.org/QuickSearch/FindTariff/FindTariff.aspx?subsite=open_access&country=566&source=1|ITC Market Access Map], an online database of customs tariffs and market requirements\n\n{{Nigeria topics}}\n{{Africa in topic|Economy of}}\n{{World Trade Organization}}\n\n[[Category:OPEC|Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Economy of Nigeria| ]]\n[[Category:World Trade Organization member economies|Nigeria]]\n[[Category:African Union member economies|Nigeria]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economy_of_Nigeria"}
{"title_page": "David Puttnam", "text_new": "{{About||the American flying Ace of [[World War I]]|David Putnam|the footballer|Dave Puttnam}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|size=100%|sep=,|post-noms= [[Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|CBE]] [[Royal Society of Arts|HonFRSA]] [[Royal Photographic Society|HonFRPS]] [[Royal Irish Academy|MRIA]]}}\n| name = The Lord Puttnam\n| image = official portrait of Lord Puttnam crop 2.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Lord Puttnam's official parliamentary photo\n|office          = Chancellor of the [[Open University]]\n|term_start      = 3 October 2007\n|term_end        = 12 March 2014\n|predecessor     = [[Betty Boothroyd|The Baroness Boothroyd]]\n|successor       = [[Martha Lane Fox|The Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho]]\n|office1         = Chancellor of the [[University of Sunderland]]\n|term_start1     = 1997\n|term_end1       = 2007\n|predecessor1    = Office established\n|successor1      = [[Steve Cram]]\n| office2          = [[Member of the House of Lords]] <br />[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start2      = 27 October 1997<br />\n[[Life Peerage]]\n| term_end2        =  \n| birth_name = David Terence Puttnam\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1941|2|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Southgate, London]], England\n| occupation = Film producer and educator\n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Patricia Mary Jones <br />|1961| |end=}}\n| children = 2\n| website = http://www.davidputtnam.com/\n}}\n\n'''David Terence Puttnam, Baron Puttnam''', {{post-nominals|size=100%|sep=,|post-noms= [[Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Royal Society of Arts|HonFRSA]], [[Royal Photographic Society|HonFRPS]], [[Royal Irish Academy|MRIA]]}} (born 25 February 1941) is a British film producer and educator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/publiclectures/lorddavidputtnam/|title=Lord David Puttnam: The Lessons of Leveson|publisher=Sunderland University|accessdate=10 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307195839/http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/publiclectures/lorddavidputtnam/|archive-date=7 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> His productions include ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'', which won the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]]. He sits on the [[Labour (UK)|Labour]] benches in the [[House of Lords]], although he is not principally a politician.\n\n==Early life==\nPuttnam was born in [[Southgate, London]], England, the son of Marie Beatrix, a homemaker of [[Jewish]] origin,<ref name=\"jpost\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Arts-and-Culture/Entertainment/Lord-David-Puttnam-reveals-the-secrets-of-the-trade|title=Lord David Puttnam reveals the secrets of the trade|work=The Jerusalem Post|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref> and Leonard Arthur Puttnam, a photographer.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/34/David-Puttnam.html Film Reference: ''David Puttnam Biography''] Retrieved 6 March 2013</ref> Educated at [[Minchenden Grammar School]] in London, Puttnam had an early career in advertising, including five formative years at [[Collett Dickenson Pearce#Famous alumni|Collett Dickenson Pearce]], and as agent acting for the photographers [[David Bailey (photographer)|David Bailey]] and [[Brian Duffy (photographer)|Brian Duffy]].\n\n==Film career==\n===Sandy Lieberson===\nHe turned to film production in the late 1960s, working with Sanford Lieberson's production company [[Goodtimes Enterprises]].\n\nThe first feature he produced was ''[[Melody (1971 film)|Melody]]'' (1971) based on a script by [[Alan Parker]], which was a minor hit.\n\nHe and Lieberson produced the documentaries ''Peacemaking 1919'' (1971), ''Glastonbury Fayre'' (1972), and ''Bringing It All Back Home'' (1972).\n\nPuttnam and Lieberson's second film, ''[[The Pied Piper (1972 film)|The Pied Piper]]'' (1972), directed by [[Jacques Demy]] was not a success, but ''[[That'll Be the Day (1973 film)|That'll Be the Day]]'' (1973) with [[David Essex]] was a hit.\n\nThey produced ''[[The Final Programme (film)|The Final Programme]]'' (1973), a science fiction film, and made some more documentaries, ''Double Headed Eagle: Hitler's Rise to Power 1918-1933'' (1973), and ''Swastika'' (1974).\n\nPuttnam and Lieberson executive produced the [[Ken Russell]] biopic ''[[Mahler (film)|Mahler]]'' (1974), and did a sequel to ''That'll Be The Day'', ''[[Stardus (1974 film)|Stardust]]'' (1974), directed by [[Michael Apted]].\n\nThere were more documentaries: ''Radio Wonderful'' (1974), ''[[Brother Can You Spare a Dime (film)|Brother Can You Spare a Dime]]'' (1975), ''[[James Dean: The First American Teenager]]'' (1975) and ''The Memory of Justice'' (1976).\n\nA second film with Russell, ''[[Lisztomania]]'' (1975), was a box office disaster and led to the end of the Puttnam-Lieberson partnership.\n\nPuttnam had a box office success with ''[[Bugsy Malone]]'' (1976), a musical he executive produced, written and directed by Alan Parker and produced by [[Alan Marshall (producer)|Alan Marshall]]. It was the last film Puttnam would make under the Goodtimes Banner. He set up a new company, Enigma Films.<ref>[https://www.duedil.com/company/01255496/enigma-productions-limited Duedil company information: ''Enigma Productions Limited'']</ref>\n\n===Enigma Films===\nPuttnam produced [[Ridley Scott]]'s debut as director, ''[[The Duellists]]'' (1977).\n\n''[[Midnight Express (film)|Midnight Express]]'' (1978) which he produced with Marshall, and was directed by Parker from a script by [[Oliver Stone]], was a notable box office success.\n\nPuttnam made his first film in America, ''[[Foxes (film)|Foxes]]'' (1980), the directorial debut of [[Adrian Lyne]]. It was a box office flop.\n\nPuttnam's next film was his most successful yet. ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' (1981), the first feature directed by [[Hugh Hudson]], became a massive hit and won the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]]. It was produced in association with [[Goldcrest Pictures]].\n\nPuttnam set up a TV company, Enigma TV, and made a series of TV movies in association with Goldcrest which carry Puttnam's name as executive producer. Six were made as a series called \"First Love\" for the fledgling Channel Four: ''[[P'tang, Yang, Kipperbang]]'' (1982), directed by Apted; ''[[Experience Preferred... But Not Essential]]'' (1982); ''[[Secrets (1983 film)|Secrets]]'' (1983); ''[[Those Glory Glory Days]]'' (1983); ''[[Sharma and Beyond]]'' (1983); and ''[[Arthur's Hallowed Ground]]'' (1984). Other films produced for television were ''[[Forever Young (1983 film)|Forever Young]]'' (1983); ''[[Red Monarch]]'' (1983); and ''[[Winter Flight]]'' (1984).\n\nPuttnam continued to produce features. He had another success with ''[[Local Hero (film)|Local Hero]]'' (1983), written and directed by [[Bill Forsyth]]. He also did the acclaimed ''[[Cal (1984 film)|Cal]]'' (1984), directed by [[Pat O'Connor (director)|Pat O'Connor]] and ''[[The Killing Fields]]'' (1984), directed by [[Roland Joffe]].\n\nHe continued to executive produce TV movies like ''[[The Frog Prince (film)|The Frog Prince]]'' (1985), ''[[Mr. Love]]'' (1985), ''[[Defence of the Realm]]'' (1986), and ''[[Knights & Emeralds]]'' (1986). He produced ''[[The Mission (1986 film)|The Mission]]'' (1986) directed by Joffe from a script by [[Robert Bolt]] which won the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in 1986).\n\n===Columbia Pictures===\nPuttnam was chairman and CEO of [[Columbia Pictures]] from June 1986 until September 1987.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/02/movies/in-re-columbia-pictures-and-puttnam-s-orphans.html|title=In Re: Columbia Pictures And Puttnam's Orphans|author=Aljean Harmetz|newspaper=New York Times|date=2 February 1989|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Post Columbia Producing Work===\nPuttnam returned to producing individual films with ''[[Memphis Belle (1990 film)|Memphis Belle]]'' (1990), ''[[Meeting Venus]]'' (1991), ''[[A Dangerous Man: Lawrence After Arabia]]'' (1992), ''[[Being Human (1994 film)|Being Human]]'' (1994), ''[[War of the Buttons (1994 film)|War of the Buttons]]'' (1994), ''[[The Confessional]]'' (1994), and ''[[My Life So Far]]'' (1995).\n\nHe executive produced ''[[The Josephine Baker Story]]'' (1991), ''[[Without Warning: The James Brady Story]]'' (1992), and ''[[The Burning Season (1994 film)|The Burning Season]]'' (1994).\n\nHe is currently overseeing pre-production of Ben Stewart\u2019s account of the Arctic 30\nincident,\u00a0Don\u2019t Trust, Don\u2019t Fear, Don\u2019t Beg. \u00a0\nHe is the President of the Film Distributors\u2019 Association; Chair of the TSL Advisory Board<ref>https://www.launchingfilms.com/about-us</ref>;\nChair of Nord Anglia International School<ref>https://www.nordangliaeducation.com/schools/dublin/international/article/2017/10/17/lord-david-puttnam-to-chair-school-advisory-board</ref>, Dublin; Life President, National Film &amp; Television\nSchool<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/david-puttnam-named-life-president-uks-national-film-tv-school-1019531</ref>, a UNICEF Ambassador<ref>https://www.unicef.org.uk/celebrity-supporters/david-puttnam/</ref>, and Adjunct Professor of Film Studies and Digital\nHumanities\u00a0at University College Cork.<ref>https://www.ucc.ie/en/news/archive/2014andbeyond/2013/puttnam-delivers-film-studies-lecture-.html</ref>\nHe is the chair of Atticus Education<ref>http://www.davidputtnam.com/masterclass-seminars</ref>, an online education company based in Ireland. Atticus\ndelivers interactive seminars on film and a variety of other subjects to educational\ninstitutions around the world.\n\n==Politics==\nIn 1983, Puttnam was appointed as a [[Commander of The Most Excellent Order of the British Empire]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=49212 |date=30 December 1982 |page=9 |supp=7}}</ref> In 1995 Puttnam was appointed as a [[Knight Bachelor]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=53893 |date=30 December 1994 |page=2| supp=2}}</ref> In 1997, Puttnam was created as a [[life peer]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54851 |date=1 August 1997 |page=8910}}</ref> and was granted Letters Patent to become '''Baron Puttnam''', of Queensgate in the [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue= 54934| date=30 October 1997 |page=12205}}</ref> In 1998, Puttnam was named in a list of financial donors to the British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/161057.stm | title= 'Luvvies' for Labour | work=BBC News | date=30 August 1998 | accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> In 2002, he chaired the joint scrutiny committee on the [[Communications Act 2003|Communications Bill]], which recommended an amendment to prevent ownership of British terrestrial TV stations by companies with a significant share of the newspaper market. This was widely interpreted as being aimed at stopping [[Rupert Murdoch]]'s [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] from buying channel [[Five (channel)|Five]]. When the government opposed the amendment, Puttnam brokered a compromise \u2013 the introduction of a \"public interest\" test to be applied by the new regulator [[Ofcom]], but without explicit restrictions.\n\nFrom 2004 to 2005, Puttnam chaired the [[Hansard Society]] Commission on Communication of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]]ary Democracy, the final report of which urged all political parties to commit to a renewal of parliamentary life in an attempt to reinvigorate representative democracy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/may/24/uk.media|title=Puttnam urges parliament to modernise|author=White, Michael|date=24 May 2005|work=The Guardian|location=London}}</ref><ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04106.pdf House of Commons Library \u2013 Standard Note \u2013 The Puttnam (Hansard Society) Commission: Members Only? Parliament in the Public Eye] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225102649/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04106.pdf |date=25 February 2009 }}</ref> In 2007, he chaired the [[Climate Change Act 2008#Pre-Legislative Scrutiny|Joint Parliamentary Committee on the Draft Climate Change Bill]].\n\nFrom 2012 to 2017, he has was the [[Prime Ministerial Trade Envoy]] to Vietnam, Laos, Cambodia and Myanmar (Burma).<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20304800|title=David Cameron: We must push in 'global trade race'|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 January 2014|date=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2012 to 2017, Puttnam, who lives in [[Skibbereen]], County Cork, was named Ireland\u2019s [[Digital Champions|Digital Champion]] by Communications Minister [[Pat Rabbitte]], TD.<ref name=\"siliconrepublic\">{{cite web|url=http://siliconrepublic.com/digital-21/item/30778-oscar-winning-producer-lord|title=Oscar-winning producer Lord David Puttnam named Ireland's Digital Champion|work=siliconrepublic.com|author=Kennedy, John|date=17 December 2012|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lord Puttnam.JPG|thumb|upright|Lord Puttnam on 10 July 2006 at the [[University of Sunderland]] School of Computing and Technology Awards Ceremony.]]\n\nIn August 2014, Puttnam was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' opposing [[Scottish independence]] in the run-up to September's [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on that issue]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text |title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Lord Puttnam was appointed chair of the special House of Lords Democracy and Digital Technologies Committee, set up to investigate the impact of digital technologies on democracy.<ref>https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?ibxr=0#inbox/FMfcgxwChchSPNGTtKJPtxGjcdJDVXGX</ref>\n\n==Association with education==\nPuttnam was for 10 years chairman of the [[National Film and Television School]] whose alumni included people such as [[Nick Park]], and in 2017, he succeeded Lord Richard Attenborough as\nLife President. He founded [[Skillset]], which trains young people to become members of the film and television industries. From 2002-2009 he was UK president of [[United Nations Children's Fund|UNICEF]] and remains an ambassador.<ref name=\"unicef\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org.uk/UNICEFs-Work/Our-supporters/Celebrities/David-Puttnam/|title=Lord David Puttnam: UNICEF UK ambassador|publisher=unicef.org.uk|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nPuttnam was the first chancellor of the [[University of Sunderland]] from 1997 until 13 July 2007. He was appointed an Honorary Doctor of Education during the School of [[Education and Lifelong Learning]]'s Academic Awards Ceremonies in his final week as Chancellor and was granted the Freedom of the City of Sunderland upon his retirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ippr.org/staff-profiles/58/638/david-puttnam|title=David Puttnam-Policy Advisory Council|publisher=IPPR|accessdate=10 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412120451/http://www.ippr.org/staff-profiles/58/638/david-puttnam|archivedate=12 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1998, he founded the National Teaching Awards and became its first chairman. He was the founding chairman of the General Teaching Council 2000\u20132002. He was appointed as chancellor of the [[Open University]] 2006-2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.open.edu/openlearn/profiles/guest-142|title=Lord David Puttnam|publisher=Open University|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref> He was also the Chairman of NESTA (The [[National Endowment for Science, Technology and the Arts]]) from 1998 until 2003. He was also on the board of directors of learning technologies company [[Promethean Ltd|Promethean]].<ref name=PrometheanWorld>{{cite web|url=http://www.prometheanworld.com/gb/english/education/about-us/leadership/ |title=Lord Puttnam, Promethean from 2006-2015, Senior Independent Director |publisher=PrometheanWorld.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209030835/http://www.prometheanworld.com/gb/english/education/about-us/leadership/ |archivedate=9 February 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nLord Puttnam is the patron of Schools NorthEast, an organisation set up in 2007 to represent all schools in the North East of England. He is also a patron of the Shakespeare Schools Festival (now Shakespeare Schools Foundation), a charity that enables school children across the UK to perform Shakespeare in professional theatres.\n\nFrom May 2014 -2018, Puttnam was Chair of the Academic Board for [[Pearson College (United Kingdom)|Pearson College]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pearsoncollege.com/about-us/chair-of-the-academicboard.html|title=Chair of the Academic Board|author=|publisher=Pearson College|date=|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> part of [[Pearson PLC]], the first [[FTSE 100 Index|FTSE 100]] company to offer degrees in the UK.\n\nIn March 2015 he was made a freeman at the Metropolitan Borough of Gateshead in recognition of his service as chairman at the Sage Gateshead.\n\nLord Puttnam is a member of the Commonwealth of Learning's Board of Governors.<ref>https://www.col.org/about/governance/current-members-cols-board-governors</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1982, he received the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] [[Michael Balcon]] Award for his outstanding contribution to the [[British Film Industry]]. In February 2006, he was awarded the BAFTA Fellowship. He made the occasion notable by delivering a particularly moving homage to his late father who had died before he received his Oscar for ''Chariots of Fire''. He also congratulated contemporary filmmakers (specifically [[George Clooney]]) for making films with integrity: the lack of such films being produced had been the reason for his retirement from the film industry in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brokeback emerges as Bafta winner |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4724066.stm |work=BBC News |date = 19 February 2006 |accessdate=8 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nLord Puttnam is the recipient of over 50 honorary degrees and fellowships from the UK and\noverseas.\n\nHe received an Honorary Doctorate from [[Heriot-Watt University]] in 2001,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www1.hw.ac.uk/annual-review/2001/our_peo_hon_grad.htm|title=Heriot-Watt University|website=www1.hw.ac.uk|access-date=2016-03-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413114505/http://www1.hw.ac.uk/annual-review/2001/our_peo_hon_grad.htm|archivedate=13 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and from Trinity College Dublin in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tcd.ie/registrar/honorary-degrees/2016-17/|title=Registrar : Trinity College Dublin, the University of Dublin, Ireland|website=www.tcd.ie|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>\n\nHe was awarded The [[Royal Photographic Society]]'s President's Medal and Honorary Fellowship (HonFRPS) in recognition of a sustained, significant contribution to the art of photography in 2003.<ref>[http://www.rps.org/annual-awards/Centenary-Medal Royal Photographic Society's Centenary Award] Accessed 13 August 2012</ref>\n\nIn May 2006, he was made an [[Honorary Fellow of the Royal Society]] of Arts. On 12 July 2007, he was given the freedom of the [[City of Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/6896448.stm | work=BBC News | title=Freedom of city for film producer | date=12 July 2007 | accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> In 2008, David received an Honorary Degree of Doctor of Science from [[Nottingham Trent University]] in recognition of his extraordinary contribution to the cultural landscape of the UK, in both economic and creative terms, and for his notable support for the Nottingham City-based GameCity Festival.<ref name=\"ntualumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntualumni.org.uk/your_alumni_association/notable_alumni/honorary_graduates/david_puttnam|title=Lord David Puttnam - Honorary graduates - Your Alumni Association - Alumni - Nottingham Trent University|publisher=ntualumni.org.uk|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> He was elected to the [[Royal Irish Academy]] in 2017. \n\nHe suffers from [[Chronic fatigue syndrome|ME]], debilitating him on occasions.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/apr/27/health.broadcasting |title=Puttnam tells of 16 years with ME |work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, in partnership with [[Sir Michael Barber]], Puttnam released ''We Are the People We've been Waiting For'' an education documentary featuring high-profile figures discussing their own experiences of education.<ref>\"{{cite web |url=http://www.wearethepeoplemovie.com/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091120071711/http://www.wearethepeoplemovie.com/ |archivedate=20 November 2009 |df=dmy-all }}\"</ref>\n\nAll in all, his films have won 10 Oscars, 25 BAFTAs and the Palme d'Or at Cannes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardiff.ac.uk/hadynellislectures/davidputtnam/index.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130615235736/http://www.cardiff.ac.uk/hadynellislectures/davidputtnam/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 June 2013 |title=2012\u2013Lord David Puttnam of Queensgate CBE, FRSA |publisher=Cardiff University |accessdate=5 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Puttnam Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Or within an orle of roses a gateway composed of a central arch between two lesse arches and surmounted by a segmental pediment Gules.\n|crest = A harp standing on a closed book fesswise Proper bound Gules.\n|supporters = Dexter, a curlew Proper gorged with a plain collar Argent charged with square billets Sable; sinister, a stork Proper gorged with a plain collar Argent charged with square billets sable.\n|motto = Servio Ut Vivam <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=2000}}</ref>}}\n\n==Other interests==\n\nPuttnam was deputy Chairman of Channel 4 Television from 2006-2012. He is president of the Film Distributors' Association (FDA) and chair of the TSL Advisory Board.\n\nPuttnam co-authored (with Neil Watson) ''Movies and Money'', published in January 2000 by Vintage Books.\n\nWhen Puttnam became the chairman of [[Profero]], a London-based digital marketing agency in April 2007, he explained the move saying: \"My experience over the past forty-odd (some very odd) years has encompassed marketing, entertainment and social issues, a fascinating mix that is integral to the daily lives of consumers and citizens. A business that can combine and magnify these dynamics can only create incredible value for their clients and, as a by-product, themselves. To me Profero is in just such a position, and it's now my job to help them realise their potential.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Lord Puttnam becomes chairman of Profero |url=http://dmweekly.mad.co.uk/Main/Home/Articlex/c07d7c1d21ff40c886c082e22f34215c/Lord-Puttnam-becomes-chairman-of-Profero.html |work=MAD |date=16 April 2007 |accessdate=13 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106122254/http://dmweekly.mad.co.uk/Main/Home/Articlex/c07d7c1d21ff40c886c082e22f34215c/Lord-Puttnam-becomes-chairman-of-Profero.html |archivedate=6 January 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nPuttnam, who had produced [[Ian Charleson]]'s star-making film ''Chariots of Fire'', contributed a chapter to the 1990 book, ''For Ian Charleson: A Tribute''.<ref>Ian McKellen, Alan Bates, Hugh Hudson, et al. [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0094702500 ''For Ian Charleson: A Tribute'']. London: Constable and Company, 1990. pp. 7\u201311.</ref>\n\nOn Sunday, 19 August 2007, Puttnam gave the oration at the annual [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]] commemoration in [[B\u00e9al na Bl\u00e1th]], [[County Cork]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1561022/Michael-Collins-was-a-peace-icon-says-Puttnam.html|title=Michael Collins was a peace icon, says Puttnam|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe has also preached at [[Durham Cathedral]] at the feast of the Cathedral's commemoration of its founders and benefactors.<ref>Durham\nCathedral website [http://www.durhamcathedral.co.uk/]</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n\nPuttnam is patron of the Irish education charity [[Camara (social enterprise)|Camara Education]]<ref name=\"camara\">{{cite web|url=http://camara.org/blog/2013/11/13/lord-puttnam-announced-patron-camara-education/|title=Lord Puttnam announced as Patron of Camara Education : Camara|publisher=camara.org|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> and [[Chronic fatigue syndrome|CFS/ME]] charity [[Action for ME]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actionforme.org.uk/get-informed/about-us/people/patrons|title=Introduction|first=|last=|website=Action for ME}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Selected filmography as producer===\n\n{{Div col}}\n*''[[Melody (1971 film)|Melody]]'' (1971)\n*''[[The Pied Piper (1972 film)|The Pied Piper]]'' (1972)\n*''[[Glastonbury Fayre (film)|Glastonbury Fayre]]'' (1972) (documentary)\n*''[[That'll Be the Day (film)|That'll Be the Day]]'' (1973)\n*''[[Mahler (film)|Mahler]]'' (1974)\n*''[[Stardust (1974 film)|Stardust]]'' (1974)\n*''[[Lisztomania (film)|Lisztomania]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Trick or Treat (unfinished film)|Trick or Treat]]'' (1975) (unfinished)\n*''[[Bugsy Malone]]'' (1976)\n*''[[The Duellists]]'' (1977)\n*''[[Midnight Express (film)|Midnight Express]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Foxes (film)|Foxes]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' (1981)\n*''[[Local Hero (film)|Local Hero]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Secrets 91983 film)|Secrets]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Sharma and Beyond]]'' (1984)\n*''[[The Killing Fields (film)|The Killing Fields]]'' (1984)\n*''[[Cal (1984 film)|Cal]]'' (1984)\n*''[[The Mission (1986 film)|The Mission]]'' (1986)\n*''[[Memphis Belle (film)|Memphis Belle]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Meeting Venus]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Being Human (1994 film)|Being Human]]'' (1994)\n*''[[War of the Buttons (1994 film)|War of the Buttons]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[My Life So Far]]'' (1999)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Some films made or bought while head of Columbia (1986\u20131988)===\n\nPuttnam [[greenlit]] and \"picked up\" a number of films while head of the studio, none of which had been released by the time he left the position. They included:<ref>Alexander Walker, ''Icons in the Fire: The Rise and Fall of Practically Everyone in the British Film Industry 1984\u20132000'', Orion Books, 2005 p60-62</ref>\n{{Div col}}\n*''[[The Big Easy (film)|The Big Easy]]'' (1986) (pick up)\n*''[[The Big Town (1987 film)|The Big Town]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Someone to Watch Over Me (film)|Someone to Watch Over Me]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Housekeeping (film)|Housekeeping]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Hope and Glory (film)|Hope and Glory]]'' (1987) (pick up)\n*''[[The Last Emperor]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Leonard Part 6]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Zelly and Me]]'' (1988)\n*''[[School Daze]]'' (1988) (pick up)\n*''[[Little Nikita]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Stars and Bars (1988 film)|Stars and Bars]]'' (1988)\n*''[[A Time of Destiny]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Vice Versa (1988 film)|Vice Versa]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Pulse (1988 film)|Pulse]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Punchline (film)|Punchline]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Vibes (film)|Vibes]]'' (1988)\n*''[[The Beast (1988 film)|The Beast]]'' (1988) (pick up)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book | author=Yule, Andrew | title=Fast Fade: David Puttnam, Columbia Pictures, and the Battle For Hollywood | url=https://archive.org/details/fastfadedavidput00yulerich | url-access=registration | publisher=Delacorte Press | year=1989 | isbn=0-440-50177-6}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|David Puttnam}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/ University of Sunderland]\n*[http://www.open.ac.uk The Open University]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091120071711/http://www.wearethepeoplemovie.com/ We are the people movie]\n*[http://www.futurelab.org.uk/about_us/meet_the_team/board_of_trustees/ Futurelab's Board of Trustees]\n*{{IMDb name|0701298|David Puttnam}}\n*{{cite news|\nurl=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/sunday_am/4729128.stm|\nwork=BBC News|\ntitle= Opening windows|\ndate=19 February 2006}} \u2013 transcript of ''Sunday AM'' interview with [[Huw Edwards (journalist)|Huw Edwards]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100122135215/http://iiea.com/events/lord-david-puttnam-at-iiea1 Speech on 'Educating for the Digital Society'] at the IIEA \u2013 19 January 2010\n*{{Internet Archive short film|id=openmind_ep1106|name=More About Movies and Money (1998)}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Sunderland]]\n| years = 1997\u20132007\n| before = First holder\n| after = [[Steve Cram]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[Open University]]\n| years = 2006\u20132014\n| before = [[Betty Boothroyd|Baroness Boothroyd]]\n| after = [[Martha Lane Fox|The Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{BAFTA Academy Fellowship Award |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Puttnam, David}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:British film producers]]\n[[Category:American film studio executives]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:BAFTA fellows]]\n[[Category:Producers who won the Best Picture Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the Open University]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Tony Blair]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Sunderland]]\n[[Category:People with chronic fatigue syndrome]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Irish Academy]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the American flying Ace of [[World War I]]|David Putnam|the footballer|Dave Puttnam}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|size=100%|sep=,|post-noms= [[Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|CBE]] [[Royal Society of Arts|HonFRSA]] [[Royal Photographic Society|HonFRPS]] [[Royal Irish Academy|MRIA]]}}\n| name = The Lord Puttnam\n| image = official portrait of Lord Puttnam crop 2.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Lord Puttnam's official parliamentary photo\n|office          = Chancellor of the [[Open University]]\n|term_start      = 3 October 2007\n|term_end        = 12 March 2014\n|predecessor     = [[Betty Boothroyd|The Baroness Boothroyd]]\n|successor       = [[Martha Lane Fox|The Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho]]\n|office1         = Chancellor of the [[University of Sunderland]]\n|term_start1     = 1997\n|term_end1       = 2007\n|predecessor1    = Office established\n|successor1      = [[Steve Cram]]\n| office2          = [[Member of the House of Lords]] <br />[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start2      = 27 October 1997<br />\n[[Life Peerage]]\n| term_end2        =  \n| birth_name = David Terence Puttnam\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1941|2|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Southgate, London]], England\n| occupation = Film producer and educator\n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Patricia Mary Jones <br />|1961| |end=}}\n| children = 2\n| website = http://www.davidputtnam.com/\n}}\n\n'''David Terence Puttnam, Baron Puttnam''', {{post-nominals|size=100%|sep=,|post-noms= [[Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Royal Society of Arts|HonFRSA]], [[Royal Photographic Society|HonFRPS]], [[Royal Irish Academy|MRIA]]}} (born 25 February 1941) is a British film producer and educator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/publiclectures/lorddavidputtnam/|title=Lord David Puttnam: The Lessons of Leveson|publisher=Sunderland University|accessdate=10 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307195839/http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/publiclectures/lorddavidputtnam/|archive-date=7 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> His productions include ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'', which won the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]]. He sits on the [[Labour (UK)|Labour]] benches in the [[House of Lords]], although he is not principally a politician.\n\n==Early life==\nPuttnam was born in [[Southgate, London]], England, the son of Marie Beatrix, a homemaker of [[Jewish]] origin,<ref name=\"jpost\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Arts-and-Culture/Entertainment/Lord-David-Puttnam-reveals-the-secrets-of-the-trade|title=Lord David Puttnam reveals the secrets of the trade|work=The Jerusalem Post|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref> and Leonard Arthur Puttnam, a photographer.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/34/David-Puttnam.html Film Reference: ''David Puttnam Biography''] Retrieved 6 March 2013</ref> Educated at [[Minchenden Grammar School]] in London, Puttnam had an early career in advertising, including five formative years at [[Collett Dickenson Pearce#Famous alumni|Collett Dickenson Pearce]], and as agent acting for the photographers [[David Bailey (photographer)|David Bailey]] and [[Brian Duffy (photographer)|Brian Duffy]].\n\n==Film career==\n===Sandy Lieberson===\nHe turned to film production in the late 1960s, working with Sanford Lieberson's production company [[Goodtimes Enterprises]].\n\nThe first feature he produced was ''[[Melody (1971 film)|Melody]]'' (1971) based on a script by [[Alan Parker]], which was a minor hit.\n\nHe and Lieberson produced the documentaries ''Peacemaking 1919'' (1971), ''Glastonbury Fayre'' (1972), and ''Bringing It All Back Home'' (1972).\n\nPuttnam and Lieberson's second film, ''[[The Pied Piper (1972 film)|The Pied Piper]]'' (1972), directed by [[Jacques Demy]] was not a success, but ''[[That'll Be the Day (1973 film)|That'll Be the Day]]'' (1973) with [[David Essex]] was a hit.\n\nThey produced ''[[The Final Programme (film)|The Final Programme]]'' (1973), a science fiction film, and made some more documentaries, ''Double Headed Eagle: Hitler's Rise to Power 1918-1933'' (1973), and ''Swastika'' (1974).\n\nPuttnam and Lieberson executive produced the [[Ken Russell]] biopic ''[[Mahler (film)|Mahler]]'' (1974), and did a sequel to ''That'll Be The Day'', ''[[Stardus (1974 film)|Stardust]]'' (1974), directed by [[Michael Apted]].\n\nThere were more documentaries: ''Radio Wonderful'' (1974), ''[[Brother Can You Spare a Dime (film)|Brother Can You Spare a Dime]]'' (1975), ''[[James Dean: The First American Teenager]]'' (1975) and ''The Memory of Justice'' (1976).\n\nA second film with Russell, ''[[Lisztomania]]'' (1975), was a box office disaster and led to the end of the Puttnam-Lieberson partnership.\n\nPuttnam had a box office success with ''[[Bugsy Malone]]'' (1976), a musical he executive produced, written and directed by Alan Parker and produced by Alan Marshall. It was the last film Puttnam would make under the Goodtimes Banner. He set up a new company, Enigma Films.<ref>[https://www.duedil.com/company/01255496/enigma-productions-limited Duedil company information: ''Enigma Productions Limited'']</ref>\n\n===Enigma Films===\nPuttnam produced [[Ridley Scott]]'s debut as director, ''[[The Duellists]]'' (1977).\n\n''[[Midnight Express (film)|Midnight Express]]'' (1978) which he produced with Marshall, and was directed by Parker from a script by [[Oliver Stone]], was a notable box office success.\n\nPuttnam made his first film in America, ''[[Foxes (film)|Foxes]]'' (1980), the directorial debut of [[Adrian Lyne]]. It was a box office flop.\n\nPuttnam's next film was his most successful yet. ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' (1981), the first feature directed by [[Hugh Hudson]], became a massive hit and won the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]]. It was produced in association with [[Goldcrest Pictures]].\n\nPuttnam set up a TV company, Enigma TV, and made a series of TV movies in association with Goldcrest which carry Puttnam's name as executive producer. Six were made as a series called \"First Love\" for the fledgling Channel Four: ''[[P'tang, Yang, Kipperbang]]'' (1982), directed by Apted; ''[[Experience Preferred... But Not Essential]]'' (1982); ''[[Secrets (1983 film)|Secrets]]'' (1983); ''[[Those Glory Glory Days]]'' (1983); ''[[Sharma and Beyond]]'' (1983); and ''[[Arthur's Hallowed Ground]]'' (1984). Other films produced for television were ''[[Forever Young (1983 film)|Forever Young]]'' (1983); ''[[Red Monarch]]'' (1983); and ''[[Winter Flight]]'' (1984).\n\nPuttnam continued to produce features. He had another success with ''[[Local Hero (film)|Local Hero]]'' (1983), written and directed by [[Bill Forsyth]]. He also did the acclaimed ''[[Cal (1984 film)|Cal]]'' (1984), directed by [[Pat O'Connor (director)|Pat O'Connor]] and ''[[The Killing Fields]]'' (1984), directed by [[Roland Joffe]].\n\nHe continued to executive produce TV movies like ''[[The Frog Prince (film)|The Frog Prince]]'' (1985), ''[[Mr. Love]]'' (1985), ''[[Defence of the Realm]]'' (1986), and ''[[Knights & Emeralds]]'' (1986). He produced ''[[The Mission (1986 film)|The Mission]]'' (1986) directed by Joffe from a script by [[Robert Bolt]] which won the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in 1986).\n\n===Columbia Pictures===\nPuttnam was chairman and CEO of [[Columbia Pictures]] from June 1986 until September 1987.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/02/movies/in-re-columbia-pictures-and-puttnam-s-orphans.html|title=In Re: Columbia Pictures And Puttnam's Orphans|author=Aljean Harmetz|newspaper=New York Times|date=2 February 1989|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Post Columbia Producing Work===\nPuttnam returned to producing individual films with ''[[Memphis Belle (1990 film)|Memphis Belle]]'' (1990), ''[[Meeting Venus]]'' (1991), ''[[A Dangerous Man: Lawrence After Arabia]]'' (1992), ''[[Being Human (1994 film)|Being Human]]'' (1994), ''[[War of the Buttons (1994 film)|War of the Buttons]]'' (1994), ''[[The Confessional]]'' (1994), and ''[[My Life So Far]]'' (1995).\n\nHe executive produced ''[[The Josephine Baker Story]]'' (1991), ''[[Without Warning: The James Brady Story]]'' (1992), and ''[[The Burning Season (1994 film)|The Burning Season]]'' (1994).\n\nHe is currently overseeing pre-production of Ben Stewart\u2019s account of the Arctic 30\nincident,\u00a0Don\u2019t Trust, Don\u2019t Fear, Don\u2019t Beg. \u00a0\nHe is the President of the Film Distributors\u2019 Association; Chair of the TSL Advisory Board<ref>https://www.launchingfilms.com/about-us</ref>;\nChair of Nord Anglia International School<ref>https://www.nordangliaeducation.com/schools/dublin/international/article/2017/10/17/lord-david-puttnam-to-chair-school-advisory-board</ref>, Dublin; Life President, National Film &amp; Television\nSchool<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/david-puttnam-named-life-president-uks-national-film-tv-school-1019531</ref>, a UNICEF Ambassador<ref>https://www.unicef.org.uk/celebrity-supporters/david-puttnam/</ref>, and Adjunct Professor of Film Studies and Digital\nHumanities\u00a0at University College Cork.<ref>https://www.ucc.ie/en/news/archive/2014andbeyond/2013/puttnam-delivers-film-studies-lecture-.html</ref>\nHe is the chair of Atticus Education<ref>http://www.davidputtnam.com/masterclass-seminars</ref>, an online education company based in Ireland. Atticus\ndelivers interactive seminars on film and a variety of other subjects to educational\ninstitutions around the world.\n\n==Politics==\nIn 1983, Puttnam was appointed as a [[Commander of The Most Excellent Order of the British Empire]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=49212 |date=30 December 1982 |page=9 |supp=7}}</ref> In 1995 Puttnam was appointed as a [[Knight Bachelor]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=53893 |date=30 December 1994 |page=2| supp=2}}</ref> In 1997, Puttnam was created as a [[life peer]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54851 |date=1 August 1997 |page=8910}}</ref> and was granted Letters Patent to become '''Baron Puttnam''', of Queensgate in the [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue= 54934| date=30 October 1997 |page=12205}}</ref> In 1998, Puttnam was named in a list of financial donors to the British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/161057.stm | title= 'Luvvies' for Labour | work=BBC News | date=30 August 1998 | accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> In 2002, he chaired the joint scrutiny committee on the [[Communications Act 2003|Communications Bill]], which recommended an amendment to prevent ownership of British terrestrial TV stations by companies with a significant share of the newspaper market. This was widely interpreted as being aimed at stopping [[Rupert Murdoch]]'s [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] from buying channel [[Five (channel)|Five]]. When the government opposed the amendment, Puttnam brokered a compromise \u2013 the introduction of a \"public interest\" test to be applied by the new regulator [[Ofcom]], but without explicit restrictions.\n\nFrom 2004 to 2005, Puttnam chaired the [[Hansard Society]] Commission on Communication of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]]ary Democracy, the final report of which urged all political parties to commit to a renewal of parliamentary life in an attempt to reinvigorate representative democracy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/may/24/uk.media|title=Puttnam urges parliament to modernise|author=White, Michael|date=24 May 2005|work=The Guardian|location=London}}</ref><ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04106.pdf House of Commons Library \u2013 Standard Note \u2013 The Puttnam (Hansard Society) Commission: Members Only? Parliament in the Public Eye] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225102649/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04106.pdf |date=25 February 2009 }}</ref> In 2007, he chaired the [[Climate Change Act 2008#Pre-Legislative Scrutiny|Joint Parliamentary Committee on the Draft Climate Change Bill]].\n\nFrom 2012 to 2017, he has was the [[Prime Ministerial Trade Envoy]] to Vietnam, Laos, Cambodia and Myanmar (Burma).<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20304800|title=David Cameron: We must push in 'global trade race'|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 January 2014|date=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2012 to 2017, Puttnam, who lives in [[Skibbereen]], County Cork, was named Ireland\u2019s [[Digital Champions|Digital Champion]] by Communications Minister [[Pat Rabbitte]], TD.<ref name=\"siliconrepublic\">{{cite web|url=http://siliconrepublic.com/digital-21/item/30778-oscar-winning-producer-lord|title=Oscar-winning producer Lord David Puttnam named Ireland's Digital Champion|work=siliconrepublic.com|author=Kennedy, John|date=17 December 2012|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lord Puttnam.JPG|thumb|upright|Lord Puttnam on 10 July 2006 at the [[University of Sunderland]] School of Computing and Technology Awards Ceremony.]]\n\nIn August 2014, Puttnam was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' opposing [[Scottish independence]] in the run-up to September's [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on that issue]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text |title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Lord Puttnam was appointed chair of the special House of Lords Democracy and Digital Technologies Committee, set up to investigate the impact of digital technologies on democracy.<ref>https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?ibxr=0#inbox/FMfcgxwChchSPNGTtKJPtxGjcdJDVXGX</ref>\n\n==Association with education==\nPuttnam was for 10 years chairman of the [[National Film and Television School]] whose alumni included people such as [[Nick Park]], and in 2017, he succeeded Lord Richard Attenborough as\nLife President. He founded [[Skillset]], which trains young people to become members of the film and television industries. From 2002-2009 he was UK president of [[United Nations Children's Fund|UNICEF]] and remains an ambassador.<ref name=\"unicef\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org.uk/UNICEFs-Work/Our-supporters/Celebrities/David-Puttnam/|title=Lord David Puttnam: UNICEF UK ambassador|publisher=unicef.org.uk|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nPuttnam was the first chancellor of the [[University of Sunderland]] from 1997 until 13 July 2007. He was appointed an Honorary Doctor of Education during the School of [[Education and Lifelong Learning]]'s Academic Awards Ceremonies in his final week as Chancellor and was granted the Freedom of the City of Sunderland upon his retirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ippr.org/staff-profiles/58/638/david-puttnam|title=David Puttnam-Policy Advisory Council|publisher=IPPR|accessdate=10 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412120451/http://www.ippr.org/staff-profiles/58/638/david-puttnam|archivedate=12 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1998, he founded the National Teaching Awards and became its first chairman. He was the founding chairman of the General Teaching Council 2000\u20132002. He was appointed as chancellor of the [[Open University]] 2006-2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.open.edu/openlearn/profiles/guest-142|title=Lord David Puttnam|publisher=Open University|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref> He was also the Chairman of NESTA (The [[National Endowment for Science, Technology and the Arts]]) from 1998 until 2003. He was also on the board of directors of learning technologies company [[Promethean Ltd|Promethean]].<ref name=PrometheanWorld>{{cite web|url=http://www.prometheanworld.com/gb/english/education/about-us/leadership/ |title=Lord Puttnam, Promethean from 2006-2015, Senior Independent Director |publisher=PrometheanWorld.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209030835/http://www.prometheanworld.com/gb/english/education/about-us/leadership/ |archivedate=9 February 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nLord Puttnam is the patron of Schools NorthEast, an organisation set up in 2007 to represent all schools in the North East of England. He is also a patron of the Shakespeare Schools Festival (now Shakespeare Schools Foundation), a charity that enables school children across the UK to perform Shakespeare in professional theatres.\n\nFrom May 2014 -2018, Puttnam was Chair of the Academic Board for [[Pearson College (United Kingdom)|Pearson College]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pearsoncollege.com/about-us/chair-of-the-academicboard.html|title=Chair of the Academic Board|author=|publisher=Pearson College|date=|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> part of [[Pearson PLC]], the first [[FTSE 100 Index|FTSE 100]] company to offer degrees in the UK.\n\nIn March 2015 he was made a freeman at the Metropolitan Borough of Gateshead in recognition of his service as chairman at the Sage Gateshead.\n\nLord Puttnam is a member of the Commonwealth of Learning's Board of Governors.<ref>https://www.col.org/about/governance/current-members-cols-board-governors</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1982, he received the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] [[Michael Balcon]] Award for his outstanding contribution to the [[British Film Industry]]. In February 2006, he was awarded the BAFTA Fellowship. He made the occasion notable by delivering a particularly moving homage to his late father who had died before he received his Oscar for ''Chariots of Fire''. He also congratulated contemporary filmmakers (specifically [[George Clooney]]) for making films with integrity: the lack of such films being produced had been the reason for his retirement from the film industry in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brokeback emerges as Bafta winner |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4724066.stm |work=BBC News |date = 19 February 2006 |accessdate=8 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nLord Puttnam is the recipient of over 50 honorary degrees and fellowships from the UK and\noverseas.\n\nHe received an Honorary Doctorate from [[Heriot-Watt University]] in 2001,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www1.hw.ac.uk/annual-review/2001/our_peo_hon_grad.htm|title=Heriot-Watt University|website=www1.hw.ac.uk|access-date=2016-03-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413114505/http://www1.hw.ac.uk/annual-review/2001/our_peo_hon_grad.htm|archivedate=13 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and from Trinity College Dublin in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tcd.ie/registrar/honorary-degrees/2016-17/|title=Registrar : Trinity College Dublin, the University of Dublin, Ireland|website=www.tcd.ie|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>\n\nHe was awarded The [[Royal Photographic Society]]'s President's Medal and Honorary Fellowship (HonFRPS) in recognition of a sustained, significant contribution to the art of photography in 2003.<ref>[http://www.rps.org/annual-awards/Centenary-Medal Royal Photographic Society's Centenary Award] Accessed 13 August 2012</ref>\n\nIn May 2006, he was made an [[Honorary Fellow of the Royal Society]] of Arts. On 12 July 2007, he was given the freedom of the [[City of Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/6896448.stm | work=BBC News | title=Freedom of city for film producer | date=12 July 2007 | accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> In 2008, David received an Honorary Degree of Doctor of Science from [[Nottingham Trent University]] in recognition of his extraordinary contribution to the cultural landscape of the UK, in both economic and creative terms, and for his notable support for the Nottingham City-based GameCity Festival.<ref name=\"ntualumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntualumni.org.uk/your_alumni_association/notable_alumni/honorary_graduates/david_puttnam|title=Lord David Puttnam - Honorary graduates - Your Alumni Association - Alumni - Nottingham Trent University|publisher=ntualumni.org.uk|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> He was elected to the [[Royal Irish Academy]] in 2017. \n\nHe suffers from [[Chronic fatigue syndrome|ME]], debilitating him on occasions.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/apr/27/health.broadcasting |title=Puttnam tells of 16 years with ME |work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, in partnership with [[Sir Michael Barber]], Puttnam released ''We Are the People We've been Waiting For'' an education documentary featuring high-profile figures discussing their own experiences of education.<ref>\"{{cite web |url=http://www.wearethepeoplemovie.com/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091120071711/http://www.wearethepeoplemovie.com/ |archivedate=20 November 2009 |df=dmy-all }}\"</ref>\n\nAll in all, his films have won 10 Oscars, 25 BAFTAs and the Palme d'Or at Cannes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardiff.ac.uk/hadynellislectures/davidputtnam/index.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130615235736/http://www.cardiff.ac.uk/hadynellislectures/davidputtnam/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 June 2013 |title=2012\u2013Lord David Puttnam of Queensgate CBE, FRSA |publisher=Cardiff University |accessdate=5 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Puttnam Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Or within an orle of roses a gateway composed of a central arch between two lesse arches and surmounted by a segmental pediment Gules.\n|crest = A harp standing on a closed book fesswise Proper bound Gules.\n|supporters = Dexter, a curlew Proper gorged with a plain collar Argent charged with square billets Sable; sinister, a stork Proper gorged with a plain collar Argent charged with square billets sable.\n|motto = Servio Ut Vivam <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=2000}}</ref>}}\n\n==Other interests==\n\nPuttnam was deputy Chairman of Channel 4 Television from 2006-2012. He is president of the Film Distributors' Association (FDA) and chair of the TSL Advisory Board.\n\nPuttnam co-authored (with Neil Watson) ''Movies and Money'', published in January 2000 by Vintage Books.\n\nWhen Puttnam became the chairman of [[Profero]], a London-based digital marketing agency in April 2007, he explained the move saying: \"My experience over the past forty-odd (some very odd) years has encompassed marketing, entertainment and social issues, a fascinating mix that is integral to the daily lives of consumers and citizens. A business that can combine and magnify these dynamics can only create incredible value for their clients and, as a by-product, themselves. To me Profero is in just such a position, and it's now my job to help them realise their potential.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Lord Puttnam becomes chairman of Profero |url=http://dmweekly.mad.co.uk/Main/Home/Articlex/c07d7c1d21ff40c886c082e22f34215c/Lord-Puttnam-becomes-chairman-of-Profero.html |work=MAD |date=16 April 2007 |accessdate=13 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106122254/http://dmweekly.mad.co.uk/Main/Home/Articlex/c07d7c1d21ff40c886c082e22f34215c/Lord-Puttnam-becomes-chairman-of-Profero.html |archivedate=6 January 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nPuttnam, who had produced [[Ian Charleson]]'s star-making film ''Chariots of Fire'', contributed a chapter to the 1990 book, ''For Ian Charleson: A Tribute''.<ref>Ian McKellen, Alan Bates, Hugh Hudson, et al. [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0094702500 ''For Ian Charleson: A Tribute'']. London: Constable and Company, 1990. pp. 7\u201311.</ref>\n\nOn Sunday, 19 August 2007, Puttnam gave the oration at the annual [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]] commemoration in [[B\u00e9al na Bl\u00e1th]], [[County Cork]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1561022/Michael-Collins-was-a-peace-icon-says-Puttnam.html|title=Michael Collins was a peace icon, says Puttnam|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe has also preached at [[Durham Cathedral]] at the feast of the Cathedral's commemoration of its founders and benefactors.<ref>Durham\nCathedral website [http://www.durhamcathedral.co.uk/]</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n\nPuttnam is patron of the Irish education charity [[Camara (social enterprise)|Camara Education]]<ref name=\"camara\">{{cite web|url=http://camara.org/blog/2013/11/13/lord-puttnam-announced-patron-camara-education/|title=Lord Puttnam announced as Patron of Camara Education : Camara|publisher=camara.org|accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> and [[Chronic fatigue syndrome|CFS/ME]] charity [[Action for ME]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actionforme.org.uk/get-informed/about-us/people/patrons|title=Introduction|first=|last=|website=Action for ME}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Selected filmography as producer===\n\n{{Div col}}\n*''[[Melody (1971 film)|Melody]]'' (1971)\n*''[[The Pied Piper (1972 film)|The Pied Piper]]'' (1972)\n*''[[Glastonbury Fayre (film)|Glastonbury Fayre]]'' (1972) (documentary)\n*''[[That'll Be the Day (film)|That'll Be the Day]]'' (1973)\n*''[[Mahler (film)|Mahler]]'' (1974)\n*''[[Stardust (1974 film)|Stardust]]'' (1974)\n*''[[Lisztomania (film)|Lisztomania]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Trick or Treat (unfinished film)|Trick or Treat]]'' (1975) (unfinished)\n*''[[Bugsy Malone]]'' (1976)\n*''[[The Duellists]]'' (1977)\n*''[[Midnight Express (film)|Midnight Express]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Foxes (film)|Foxes]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' (1981)\n*''[[Local Hero (film)|Local Hero]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Secrets 91983 film)|Secrets]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Sharma and Beyond]]'' (1984)\n*''[[The Killing Fields (film)|The Killing Fields]]'' (1984)\n*''[[Cal (1984 film)|Cal]]'' (1984)\n*''[[The Mission (1986 film)|The Mission]]'' (1986)\n*''[[Memphis Belle (film)|Memphis Belle]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Meeting Venus]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Being Human (1994 film)|Being Human]]'' (1994)\n*''[[War of the Buttons (1994 film)|War of the Buttons]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[My Life So Far]]'' (1999)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Some films made or bought while head of Columbia (1986\u20131988)===\n\nPuttnam [[greenlit]] and \"picked up\" a number of films while head of the studio, none of which had been released by the time he left the position. They included:<ref>Alexander Walker, ''Icons in the Fire: The Rise and Fall of Practically Everyone in the British Film Industry 1984\u20132000'', Orion Books, 2005 p60-62</ref>\n{{Div col}}\n*''[[The Big Easy (film)|The Big Easy]]'' (1986) (pick up)\n*''[[The Big Town (1987 film)|The Big Town]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Someone to Watch Over Me (film)|Someone to Watch Over Me]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Housekeeping (film)|Housekeeping]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Hope and Glory (film)|Hope and Glory]]'' (1987) (pick up)\n*''[[The Last Emperor]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Leonard Part 6]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Zelly and Me]]'' (1988)\n*''[[School Daze]]'' (1988) (pick up)\n*''[[Little Nikita]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Stars and Bars (1988 film)|Stars and Bars]]'' (1988)\n*''[[A Time of Destiny]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Vice Versa (1988 film)|Vice Versa]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Pulse (1988 film)|Pulse]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Punchline (film)|Punchline]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Vibes (film)|Vibes]]'' (1988)\n*''[[The Beast (1988 film)|The Beast]]'' (1988) (pick up)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book | author=Yule, Andrew | title=Fast Fade: David Puttnam, Columbia Pictures, and the Battle For Hollywood | url=https://archive.org/details/fastfadedavidput00yulerich | url-access=registration | publisher=Delacorte Press | year=1989 | isbn=0-440-50177-6}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|David Puttnam}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.sunderland.ac.uk/ University of Sunderland]\n*[http://www.open.ac.uk The Open University]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091120071711/http://www.wearethepeoplemovie.com/ We are the people movie]\n*[http://www.futurelab.org.uk/about_us/meet_the_team/board_of_trustees/ Futurelab's Board of Trustees]\n*{{IMDb name|0701298|David Puttnam}}\n*{{cite news|\nurl=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/sunday_am/4729128.stm|\nwork=BBC News|\ntitle= Opening windows|\ndate=19 February 2006}} \u2013 transcript of ''Sunday AM'' interview with [[Huw Edwards (journalist)|Huw Edwards]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100122135215/http://iiea.com/events/lord-david-puttnam-at-iiea1 Speech on 'Educating for the Digital Society'] at the IIEA \u2013 19 January 2010\n*{{Internet Archive short film|id=openmind_ep1106|name=More About Movies and Money (1998)}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Sunderland]]\n| years = 1997\u20132007\n| before = First holder\n| after = [[Steve Cram]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[Open University]]\n| years = 2006\u20132014\n| before = [[Betty Boothroyd|Baroness Boothroyd]]\n| after = [[Martha Lane Fox|The Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{BAFTA Academy Fellowship Award |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Puttnam, David}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:British film producers]]\n[[Category:American film studio executives]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:BAFTA fellows]]\n[[Category:Producers who won the Best Picture Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the Open University]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Tony Blair]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Sunderland]]\n[[Category:People with chronic fatigue syndrome]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Irish Academy]]\n", "name_user": "Gallicrow", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSandy Lieberson:Linkified \"Alan Marshall\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Puttnam"}
{"title_page": "Lebanese cuisine", "text_new": "{{short description|Culinary traditions of Lebanon}}\n[[File:Restauranthouder bij zijn shoarma spit, Bestanddeelnr 255-6509.jpg|thumb|A restaurateur with his shawarma [[Rotisserie|spit]], taken in [[Beirut]], Lebanon (1950)]]\n[[File:Mixed Plate (3186676853).jpg|thumb|Notable Lebanese dishes: [[Hummus]], [[Falafel]], [[Baba Ghanoush|Baba ghanoush]], [[Tabbouleh]], [[Shawarma]], [[Kafta]] and [[Kibbeh]]  ]]\n\n'''Lebanese cuisine''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0637\u0628\u062e \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a}}) is the culinary traditions and practices originating from [[Lebanon]]. It includes an abundance of [[whole grain]]s, [[fruit]]s, [[vegetable]]s, [[starches]], fresh [[Fish (food)|fish]] and [[seafood]]; animal fats are consumed sparingly. [[Poultry]] is eaten more often than [[red meat]], and when red meat is eaten, it is usually [[lamb and mutton|lamb]] on the coastal regions, and [[goat meat]] in the mountain regions. It also includes copious amounts of [[garlic]] and [[olive oil]], often seasoned by [[lemon juice]]. Chickpeas and parsley are also staples of the Lebanese diet.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheehan|first=Sean|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BrEG42oO2fgC&q=lebanese+chickpeas&dq=lebanese+chickpeas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi25K-9xsXoAhU7ThUIHffIAPgQ6AEIwgEwEg|title=Lebanon|date=1996-09|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-0283-1|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWell known savoury dishes include [[baba ghanouj]], a dip made of char-grilled [[eggplant]]; [[falafel]], small deep-fried patties made of highly spiced ground [[chickpeas]], fava beans, or a combination of the two; and [[shawarma]], a sandwich with marinated meat skewered and cooked on large rods. An important component of many Lebanese meals is [[hummus]], a dip or spread made of blended [[chickpeas]], sesame [[tahini]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]], typically eaten with pita bread.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kayyali|first=Randa A.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w2rc0RI7EqYC&pg=PA84&dq=lebanese+cuisine&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC3vXtxsXoAhWtShUIHR8TDZsQ6AEIrwMwMQ#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20cuisine&f=false|title=The Arab Americans|date=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-33219-7|language=en}}</ref> A well known dessert is [[baklava]], which is made of layered filo pastry filled with [[nut (fruit)|nuts]] and steeped in date syrup or honey. Some desserts are specifically prepared on special occasions: the ''[[meghli]]'', for instance, is served to celebrate a newborn baby in the family.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gall|first=Timothy L.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZLhZAAAAYAAJ&q=meghli+lebanon&dq=meghli+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwio5J2yr8LoAhVzQUEAHaKJC9sQ6AEITjAE|title=Worldmark Encyclopedia of Cultures and Daily Life|last2=Hobby|first2=Jeneen|date=2009|publisher=Gale|isbn=978-1-4144-4892-3|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Mouzawak|first=Kamal|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2P76CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT155&dq=meghli+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjoury1x8XoAhUESRUIHTjRAHgQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=meghli%20lebanon&f=false|title=Lebanese Home Cooking: Simple, Delicious, Mostly Vegetarian Recipes from the Founder of Beirut's Souk El Tayeb Market|date=2015-09-15|publisher=Quarry Books|isbn=978-1-63159-037-5|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Arak (distilled beverage)|Arak]], an anise-flavored liqueur, is the Lebanese national drink and usually served with a traditional convivial Lebanese meal. Another historic and traditional drink is [[Lebanese wine]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zurayk|first=Rami|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3lk-AQAAIAAJ&q=lebanese+arak&dq=lebanese+arak&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwip8d7Ex8XoAhU6UhUIHYpiAioQ6AEIVzAG|title=From \u02bbAkk\u0101r to \u02bbAmel: Lebanon's slow food trail : places, products and producers from Lebanon|last2=Rahman|first2=Sami Abdul|date=2008|publisher=Slow Food Beirut|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kuntz|first=Blair|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b5ptAAAAMAAJ&q=lebanese+wine&dq=lebanese+wine&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHlb3Vx8XoAhWCqHEKHVkMBQEQ6AEIlgEwDg|title=Lebanon: an insider's guide|date=2000|publisher=Prana Publishers|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Caption- Boys baking bread, Sidon orphanage. (9293979201).jpg|alt=|[[Sidonians]] baking bread in a Saida orphanage (1919-1920)|thumb]]\nLebanese cuisine is an ancient one and part of the cuisine of the [[Levantine cuisine|Levant]]. Many dishes in Lebanese cuisine can be traced back thousands of years to eras of [[Ancient Rome|Roman]], [[Ancient Egypt]]ian, [[Phoenicia under Babylonian rule|Babylonian]], [[Phoenicia under Assyrian rule|Assyrian]], [[Hittites|Hittite]] and [[Phoenicia]]n rule.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mDnQwCJXUowC&q=babylonian+lebanon&dq=babylonian+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjfhdL4x8XoAhVKShUIHd_KCCEQ6AEIzQEwFA|title=Lebanon a country study|date=1989|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, Lebanese cuisine was influenced by the different foreign civilizations that held power. From 1516 to 1918, the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]] controlled Lebanon and introduced a variety of foods that have become staples in the Lebanese diet, such as cooking with [[lamb and mutton|lamb]]. After the Ottomans were defeated in [[World War I]] (1914\u20131918), [[France]] took control of Lebanon until 1943, when the country achieved its independence. The [[France|French]] introduced foods such as [[Flan (pie)|flan]], a [[caramel custard]] dessert dating back to the 16th century AD, [[eclairs]], [[french fries]] and [[croissant]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YEcLaAEACAAJ&dq=history+of+lebanese+food&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjlh_218_zQAhXMTSYKHRHfB9kQ6AEIGjAA|title=The Culinary Heritage of Lebanon|last=Choueiri|first=Ramzi N.|date=2002-01-01|publisher=Ramzi Choueiri|isbn=9789953007533|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Lebanese diaspora]] who live worldwide have introduced new foods, spices and culinary practices into Lebanese cuisine, keeping the cuisine innovative and renowned both beyond and within its borders.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hannam|first=Kevin|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cHTDCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA136&dq=lebanese+food+worldwide&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjJlerR1MLoAhVIKuwKHYm0AbEQ6AEIPzAD#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20food%20worldwide&f=false|title=Event Mobilities: Politics, place and performance|last2=Mostafanezhad|first2=Mary|last3=Rickly|first3=Jillian|date=2016-03-17|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-45047-4|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\n\nMost often foods are grilled, baked or saut\u00e9ed in olive oil; butter or cream is rarely used other than in a few desserts. Vegetables are often eaten raw, pickled, or cooked. Like most Mediterranean countries, much of what the Lebanese eat is dictated by the seasons and what is available. Lebanese cuisine also varies by region. South Lebanon is famous for its Kibbe, the Bekaa Valley for its meat pastries (such as [[Sfiha]]), and north Lebanon and Saida (Sidon) for its sweets.  \n{{multiple image\n| perrow = 2\n| total_width = 300\n| image1 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6517.jpg\n| image2 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6520.jpg\n| image3 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6518.jpg\n| image4 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6519.jpg\n| footer = Typical Lebanese dining, with [[mezze]] and wine, taken in a restaurant in Beirut, Lebanon (1950)\n| align = \n| direction = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| caption2 = \n}}\n\nIn [[Lebanon]], very rarely are drinks served without being accompanied by food. Similar to the [[tapas]] of [[Spain]], ''mezeluri'' of [[Romania]] and aperitivo of [[Italy]], ''[[mezze]]'' is an array of small dishes placed before the guests creating an array of colors, flavors, textures and aromas.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Walker|first=Harlan|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GsNyprRS7EIC&pg=PA268&dq=history+of+mezze&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj_iL_VyMXoAhUCUxUIHQYaAicQ6AEIPzAD#v=onepage&q=history%20of%20mezze&f=false|title=The Meal: Proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery, 2001|date=2002|publisher=Oxford Symposium|isbn=978-1-903018-24-8|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Cavendish\">{{Cite book|last=Cavendish|first=Marshall|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j894miuOqc4C&pg=PA979&dq=lebanese+mezze&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyhrSMsMLoAhUTecAKHaCEAWwQ6AEIUDAF#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20mezze&f=false|title=World and Its Peoples|date=September 2006|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-7571-2|language=en}}</ref> This style of serving food is less a part of family life than it is of entertaining and caf\u00e9s. Mezze may be as simple as raw or [[pickled vegetables]], [[hummus]], [[baba ghanouj]] and bread, or it may become an entire meal consisting of grilled marinated [[seafood]], skewered meats, a variety of cooked and raw salads and an arrangement of desserts. Family cuisine offers also a range of dishes, such as stews (or yakhneh), which can be cooked in many forms depending on the ingredients used and are usually served with [[meat]] and rice vermicelli. [[Pita]] bread is a [[staple food|staple]] of every Lebanese meal, and can be used in place of a fork.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cavendish|first=Marshall|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j894miuOqc4C&pg=PA979&dq=lebanese+mezze&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSspGhyMXoAhXSURUIHeb4Bg8Q6AEIUDAF#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20mezze&f=false|title=World and Its Peoples|date=2006|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|year=|isbn=978-0-7614-7571-2|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlthough simple fresh fruits are often served towards the end of a Lebanese meal, there is also [[dessert]], such as [[baklava]] and [[coffee]]. Although baklava is the most internationally known dessert, there is a great variety of Lebanese desserts.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hamadeh|first=Mona|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R0qWBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA211&dq=lebanese+desserts&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj7npbzyMXoAhVaURUIHU4NBv4Q6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20desserts&f=false|title=A Lebanese Feast of Vegetables, Pulses, Herbs and Spices|date=2015-08-06|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84528-580-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA typical ''[[mezze]]'' will consist of an elaborate variety of thirty hot and cold dishes and may include:\n\n* Salads such as [[tabbouleh]] and [[fattoush]], together with dip such as [[hummus]], [[baba ghanoush]] or ''moutabal'', and [[kebbeh]],\n* Some patties such as the [[sambusac]],\n*[[Stuffed grape leaves]] and pickles,\n* Roasted nuts, olives and vegetables; served with condiments like [[toum]] and [[Tarator|taratour]], ideal for spread on [[sfiha]].<ref name=\"Cavendish\"/><ref>{{Cite book|last=Rombauer|first=Irma S.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jcq2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&dq=mezze+nuts&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4oKvIycXoAhXOQxUIHZi-DWMQ6AEIQTAD#v=onepage&q=mezze%20nuts&f=false|title=Joy of Cooking: 2019 Edition Fully Revised and Updated|last2=Becker|first2=Marion Rombauer|last3=Becker|first3=Ethan|last4=Becker|first4=John|last5=Scott|first5=Megan|date=2019-11-12|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-5011-6971-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe assortments of dishes forming the mezze are generally consumed in small bites using a piece of Lebanese bread ([[khubz]], [[pita]]) or a fork. As a family, it is made up of three or four dishes, but in the restaurant, the mezze can range from twenty to sixty dishes, as the varient combinations and dishes involved are plenty.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jousiffe|first=Ann|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q7IUAQAAIAAJ&q=lebanese+mezze+dishes&dq=lebanese+mezze+dishes&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiO2oO_zcXoAhXWQRUIHYFtCFQQ6AEIeTAK|title=Lebanon|date=1998|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-0-86442-350-4|language=en}}</ref><gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"200\" heights=\"170\" mode=\"packed-overlay\" caption=\"''A selection of well-known dishes within the Lebanese cuisine:''\">\nFile:Palestinianbreakfastfalafel.jpg|[[Falafel]], with hummus, [[Pita]] and various vegetables\nFile:Byblos Harbour, Millwall, London (3639283205).jpg|From left to right: [[Hummus]], [[Ful medames]] (fava bean stew), [[Batata harra]] (spicy potatoes) and [[Moussaka]]\nFile:Kibbeh Nayyeh.jpg|[[Kibbeh nayyeh]]\nFile:Petit assortiment de nourriture libanaise (Lyon, 2017).jpg|Assortment of nutritious Lebanese food, served in Lyon, [[France]]\nFile:Sheikhmahshe.JPG|Sheikh Mahshi served with rice\nFile:Mixedlebanesefood.JPG|Clockwise from bottom right: [[Kafta]] (grilled spiced ground meat), [[Balila (dish)|Balila]] (boiled chickpeas in lemon and garlic dressing), [[Tabbouleh]] and [[Mashawi]] (barbecued spiced meat)\nFile:Tabbouleh2.JPG|Lebanese [[Tabbouleh]] served with lettuce\nFile:Sayadiyah Fish.jpg|Sayadieh Samak (baked fish with rice)\n</gallery>\n\n==Dishes and ingredients==\n[[File:Baklava - Turkish special, 80-ply.JPEG|thumb|Mediterranean-style baklava]]\n[[File:Fatethomos.JPG|thumb|Lebanese Fateh b'hummus|alt=]]\n[[File:Ful medames (arabic meal).jpg|thumb|Fava bean stew, or [[Ful medames]] (Lebanese Style)]]\n[[File:Ftayerbelefet.JPG|thumb|Ftayer be sbenigj ([[spinach|spin]][[spinach|ach]] [[turnover (food)|turnovers]])]]\n[[File:Fattoush.JPG|alt=|thumb|[[Fattoush]]]]\n[[File:Sfiha2.jpg|thumb|[[Sfiha]], a pie-like dish from the Lebanese town of [[Baalbek]]]]\n\n* [[Ackawi cheese|Ackawi]] - white cheese salty or not depending on choice.\n* [[Halloum cheese|Halloum]] - white cheese salty, can be grilled.\n* [[Baba ghanouj]] - char-grilled ''aubergine'' ([[eggplant]]), [[tahina]], [[olive oil]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]] puree\u2014served as a dip.\n* [[Batata harra]] - spicy cube potatoes fried.\n* [[Baklava]] - a dessert of layered pastry filled with [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s and steeped in Attar syrup ([[Orange (fruit)|orange]] or rose water and [[sugar]]), usually cut in a triangular or diamond shape that originates in Lebanon,   it is a rich, sweet pastry made of layers of filo pastry filled with chopped nuts and sweetened with syrup or honey .\n* [[Roasting|Roasted]] [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]] - a mix of more than 20 kinds and flavors of [[kernels]], mostly dry roasted.\n* [[Balila]] - known as [[cumin]] [[chickpeas]].\n* [[Barout del batata]] - spicy lamb served with potatoes.\n* [[Chawarma lahmeh]] -  grilled meat with parsley, onion and tarator (served as a sandwich or a plat.)\n* [[Chawarma djeij]] -  grilled poultry with toum (garlic) and lettuce (served as a sandwich or a plat.)\n* [[Chich Taouk]] - grilled chicken marinated with garlic lemon and various oriental spices (cinnamon, cumin...)\n* [[Daoud Bacha]] - meatballs with tomato sauce.\n* [[Djaj Mechwi]] - grilled chicken on bbq marinated with a garlic lemon sauce.\n* [[Fattoush]] - 'peasant' salad of toasted pita bread, [[cucumbers]], [[tomatoes]], [[chickweed]], and [[Mentha|mint]].\n* [[Falafel]] - small deep-fried patties made of highly-spiced ground [[chickpeas]].\n* [[Fried cauliflower]] - served with tarator sauce.\n* [[Fried eggplant]]\n* [[Fatteh]] - [[chickpeas]], [[yogurt]], [[minced meat]], spices and grilled Lebanese pita cut in triangle.\n* [[Ful medames|Fuul]] (''[[vicia faba]]'') slow cooked mash of brown [[beans]] and red [[lentils]] dressed with [[lemon]], [[olive oil]] and [[cumin]].\n* [[Halva]] - sesame paste sweet, usually made in a slab and studded with [[fruit]] and [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s.\n* [[Hummus]] - dip or spread made of blended [[chickpeas]], sesame [[tahini]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]], and typically eaten with pita bread.\n* [[Hummus ras aasfour]] - dip made of blended [[chickpeas]], sesame [[tahini]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]], with meat on top, eaten with pita bread.\n* [[Jwenih]] - chicken wings cooked with coriander, garlic and lemon, served as mezze.\n* [[Kanafeh|Kunafi]] - either shoelace pastry dessert stuffed with sweet [[white cheese]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2020}}, [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s and [[syrup]], or more commonly the version with semolina pastry served on a [[sesame seed]] bun with sweet sugar syrup (very popular for breakfast) made with \" angel hair\" butter and pistachios or nuts. Generally these can be found in sweet shops, as well as bigger bakeries.\n* [[Kibbeh]] - the national dish, mainly stuffed, can be made in different forms including fried, uncooked, and cooked with [[yogurt]].\n* [[Kibbeh nayyeh]] - raw kibbeh eaten like [[steak]] tartar.\n* [[Kofta]] - fingers, stars or a flat cake of [[Ground meat|minced meat]] and [[spices]] that can be baked or charcoal-grilled on skewers.\n* [[Kousa Mahshi]]- stuffed [[zucchini]], many varieties are used.\n* [[Kubideh]] - served with ''[[pivaz]]'' (a mix of minced [[parsley]], [[onions]], ground [[cumin]] and [[sumac]]).\n* [[Labneh]]- strained yogurt, spreadable and garnished with good olive oil and [[sea salt]].\n* [[Labneh we toum]] - strained yogurt mixed with garlic, spreadable and garnished with good olive oil and [[sea salt]].\n* [[Ladies' fingers|Znood Es-sett]] - filo pastry cigars with various fillings.\n* [[Sfiha|Lahm bil aj\u0129n]] - a pastry covered with [[Ground meat|minced meat]], [[onions]], and [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]].\n* [[Ma'amoul]] -  cake made from semolina with [[date (fruit)|date]], [[pistachio]] or [[walnut]] filled cookies shaped in a wooden mould called a ''tabi'' made specially for Christian (traditionally Eastern) and Muslim holidays (such as [[Ramadan]]).\n* [[Mfaraket Koussa]] spicy zucchini.\n* [[Manakousheh zaatar]] thyme pizza usually served for breakfast.\n* [[Manakousheh jebneh]] only cheese Lebanese pizza usually served for breakfast.\n* [[Lahm bi ajain]] (also called mankhoucheh lahmeh) - minced meat with tomatoes and onion, usually served with yogurt drink\n* [[Makdous]] - stuffed eggplant in olive oil.\n* [[Manaeesh]] - mini pizzas that are made in any number of local bakeries or Furns (Furn Assalam, Ain El Hilwe, Saida), traditionally garnished with [[cheese]], [[Za'atar]], spicy diced tomatoes, [[kashk]] in its Lebanese version, or minced meat and onions. Some bakeries allow you to bring your own toppings and build your own or buy the ones they sell there. Breakfast, lunch and dinner.\n* [[Mujaddara]] (''imjaddarra'') - cooked [[lentils]] together with [[wheat]] or [[rice]], garnished with onions that have been 'sauteed' (lightly cooked in vegetable oil).\n* [[Mulukhiyah]] - A stew with mallow leaves, [[chicken]], [[beef]], and in the Lebanese fashion, topped with raw chopped onions, and [[vinegar]] over rice. It sometimes has toasted pita chips under the rice.\n* [[Mutabbel]] - made from eggplant.\n* [[Pastirma]] - cured, seasoned dried beef.[[File:Kibbetbatata.JPG|thumb|Kibbet batata ([[potato]] [[kibbeh]])]]\n* [[Qawarma]] - chopped lamb, salted and kept in the grease of the animal.\n* [[Samkeh Harra]] - grilled [[fish]] that has been marinated with [[Chili pepper|chili]], [[citrus]], and [[cilantro]]\n* [[Shanklish]] - aged cheese balls.\n* [[Shawarma]] - marinated meat (either [[chicken]] or [[lamb and mutton|lamb]]) that is skewered on big rods and cooked slowly, then shaved and placed in a 10&nbsp;inch pita roll with [[pickling|pickles]], [[tomatoes]], and other tangy condiments.\n* [[Shish taouk]]- grilled chicken skewers that utilize only white meat, marinated in olive oil, lemon, parsley, and sumac.\n* [[Siyyadiyeh]] - delicately spiced fish served on a bed of rice. Fish cooked in [[saffron]] and served on rice with [[onions]], [[sumac]], and a [[tahini]] sauce (the most important part of the dish) originated in Saida (sidon).\n* [[Sfiha]] - a dish from the Lebanese town of [[Baalbek]].\n* [[Tabbouleh]] - diced parsley salad with [[burghul]], [[tomato]] and [[Mentha|mint]].\n* [[Tahini]] - sesame paste.\n* [[Toum]] - garlic sauce.\n* [[Dolma|Wara' Enab]] (''dolma'') - stuffed grape leaves.\n* [[Za'atar]] - dried [[thyme]] and sumac that can differ from region to region and from family to family. Most are made in house, but can be bought at Lebanese larders.\n* Lebanese Spice Blend - a mixture of equal parts of [[allspice]], [[black pepper]], [[cinnamon]], [[cloves]], [[fenugreek]], [[nutmeg]] and [[ginger]]. It is commonly used to flavor many Lebanese dishes.\n\n== Sweets ==\n[[File:Middle eastern sweets.jpg|alt=|thumb|Selection of Lebanese sweets made in S\u00e3o Paulo, [[Brazil]], sold by one of the many Lebanese restaurants within the Brazilian [[Lebanese diaspora]]|left]]\n[[File:Atayebasafeeri.JPG|thumb|Modern presentation of Lebanese dessert ''[[qatayef]] asafiri'' |alt=]]\nThe modern form of Lebanese desserts have been influenced by [[Ottoman cuisine]] and share many similarties with other Levantine countries, including [[muhallebi]], a milk [[pudding]] made with rice, milk and sugar. Like many other Lebanese desserts it is sweetened with ''[[atar]]'' syrup and served with a garnish of assorted nuts.<ref name=\"sweets\">{{cite book |last1=Roufs |first1=Timothy G. |last2=Roufs |first2=Kathleen Smyth |title=Sweet Treats Around the World |pages=179\u2013183}}</ref>\n\n''[[Barazeh]]'', also found in [[Syrian cuisine]], are cookies with a light and crumbly texture; one size is decorated with sesame seeds and the other [[pistachio]]. ''[[Ma'amoul]]'' are crumbly cookies filled with pistachio, walnuts or [[Dates (fruit)|dates]]. [[Lebanese Christians]] serve ''ma'amoul'' with ''atar'' syrup for Easter, as well as a cake flavored with [[anise]] and ''[[mahlab]]''.<ref name=\"sweets\" />[[File:Lebanon - Baklava - Karabij - Eclair (2318962553).jpg|thumb|Mix of Lebanese desserts incuding [[Baklava]], [[\u00c9clair]], Karabij and others]]\n\nPastry shops in Tripoli offer the common ''[[baklava]]'' along with other local specialty pastries like ''halawet al jibn'', filled with sweetened cheese and topped with ''atar'', pistachios, [[clotted cream]] (''ashta'') and [[rose jam]]. ''Znoud al-sit'', a syrup-soaked rolled pastry filled with clotted cream and garnished in typical fashion with nuts, orange peels and [[Dates (fruit)|dates]] to the 19th century.<ref name=\"sweets\" />\n\n[[Semolina]] is used in the preparation of several Lebanese desserts like the pistachio-filled cookie ''[[karabeej|karabij]]'' (or aleppo cookies), flavored with ''[[mahlab]]'' and cinnamon, and served with ''[[natef]]'', a topping similar to [[meringue]]. ''[[Mafroukeh]]'' is a semolina dough layered with caramel and butter, soaked in ''atar'' and served with clotted cream and assorted nuts. It can also be used to make cakes like ''[[basbousa|nammoura]]''.<ref name=sweets/>\n\nDesserts include pastries such as [[Aish as-Saraya]], [[Qatayef]], [[Basbousa]], [[Harees]], [[Kanafeh]], [[baklava]], [[Ka'ak]], [[Sfouf]] and [[Maamoul]]. Lebanese [[ice cream]] is popular with its oriental flavors, including [[Qamar al-Din|Amar al-Din]] made from dried apricots (can also be eaten as a snack); fresh fruits, and pistachio. Lebanese roasted [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]] with a variety of different mixes and flavours can be eaten before, during and after meals.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hamadeh|first=Mona|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R0qWBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA211&dq=lebanese+desserts&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj7npbzyMXoAhVaURUIHU4NBv4Q6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20desserts&f=false|title=A Lebanese Feast of Vegetables, Pulses, Herbs and Spices|date=2015-08-06|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84528-580-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== By region ==\n{{Culture of region\n| name          = Culture of Lebanon\n| region        = Lebanon\n| image         = Flag-map of Lebanon.svg\n| imagesize     = 150\n| cuisoverride  = Lebanese cuisine\n}}\nThese recipes are attributed to these regions in Lebanon, although you find them now as main dishes at most Lebanese homes across the country with local variations.\n\n*Ain-Zibdeh: Hareeseh (wheat and beef)\n*[[Ajaltoun]]: Maakroun bi Thineh (Pastry boiled to which is added lemon and Thineh)\n*[[Aley]]: Tabbouleh bi Dehn (cooked tabouleh with lentils with beef ghee)\n*[[Baalbek]]: Safiha Baalbakieh (meat-stuffed puff pastry)\n*Baino: Kebbe and Lahme bil-khal (meat mixed with crushed wheat and meat soaked in vinegar)\n*[[Baskinta]]: Makhlouta (meat, rice, and nuts)\n*[[Beirut]]: Samkeh Harra and Akhtabout (spicy fish and octopus), Roastuts\n*[[Beit Chabab]]: Riz bi-Djaj (chicken with rice)\n*[[Beit Mery]]: Kebbe Lakteen (pumpkin-flavoured meat)\n*[[Beiteddine]]: Kafta Bithine (spiced meat with sesame concentrate)\n*[[Broummana]]: Deleh Mehshi (stuffed rib cage of lamb)\n*[[Bsharri]]: Koussa bil-Laban (meat and rice-stuffed zucchini cooked in yoghurt)\n*[[Dhour El Choueir]]: [[Shishbarak|Shish Barak]] (dough balls stuffed with ground beef and cooked in yoghurt)\n*[[Douma, Lebanon|Douma]]: Laban Immo (cooked yoghurt and lamb with rice)\n*[[Ehden]]: Kebbe Zghartweih (oven-cooked meat and crushed wheat blend)\n*[[El-Koura|El Koura]]: Abu Shoushe (taro and lentils stew)\n* Ferzol: [[Freekeh|Freikeh]] (cooked wheat with meat)\n*[[Hammana]]: Fasoulya Hammanieh (kidney bean stew)\n* Hrajel: Zaatar baladi (Thym with sesame, salt and olive oil)\n* Ihmej: Ghameh (stuffed cow intestines)\n*[[Jbeil]]: Koussa and Wark Inab bil-Kastaletah (stuffed zucchini, grape vines and steak)\n* Kifar meshki: Kebbe bil-Kishk (meat mixed with wheat and yoghurt)\n*[[Marjayoun]]: Vine leaves with squash and grilled chicken\n*[[Nabatieh]]: [[Sfiha]] (open-faced [[meat pie]]s made with ground [[mutton]]\n*[[Al-Qalamoun|Qalamoun]]: Fresh Carrot juice with ice cream inside\n*[[Ras el-Matn|Ras El Matn]]: Fatet (yoghurt, fried bread and nuts)\n* Rashana: Mjadrat Fasoulya (lentils and kidney beans)\n*[[Rashaya|Rashaya Al Wadi]]: Kebbe Heeleh (meatballs)\n* Saghbeen and [[Machghara]]: Zinkoul bil-Laban (meat filled pastry and yoghurt)\n*[[Shouf]]: Fatet Batinjan (yoghurt, fried bread and aubergine) and [[mate (beverage)|mate]]\n*[[Sidon]]: Riz bil-Foul (Rice and fava beans)\n*[[Tripoli, Lebanon]]: Mjadrah and Fattoush (crushed lentils and salad)\n*[[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]: Saiyadit al-Samak (rice and fish)\n*[[Zahl\u00e9]]: Kebbe Zahleweieh (meat and crushed wheat blend)\n\n== Beverages ==\n\n*[[Arabic coffee]]\n*[[Almaza Beer|Beer]], alcoholic beverage{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| total_width = 620\n| image_style = border:none;\n| image1 = Arabic coffee.jpg\n| alt1 = Arabic coffee\n| caption1 = [[Arabic coffee]]\n| image2 = Arak with water and ice.jpg\n| alt2 = Arak with water and ice\n| caption2 = [[Arak (drink)|Arak]] with water and ice\n| image3 = Jallab.jpg\n| alt3 = Jallab\n| caption3 = [[Jallab]], made from [[carob]], [[Date palm|dates]], grape [[molasses]] and [[rose water]]\n| image4 = Coffee Syria 2.jpg\n| alt4 = Black Coffee\n| caption4 = Lebanese style black coffee\n}}\n*[[Arak (liqueur)|Arak]], alcoholic beverage\n*[[Ayran]], yogurt\n*[[Coffee|Black coffee]]\n*[[Ceratonia siliqua|Le caroubier]], non-alcoholic beverage made from carob\n*[[Jallab]], sweet drink\n*[[Lebanese wine]], alcoholic beverage\n*[[Mate (beverage)|Mate]] in [[Shouf]] and [[Aley]]\n*[[Turkish coffee]]\n\n== Lebanese wine ==\n{{See also|Lebanese wine|Phoenicians and wine}}\n[[File:Grape presses and jars from the wedding of Qana.jpg|thumb|Grape presses and jars from the [[Marriage at Cana]], the first miracle attributed to [[Jesus]], Located in [[Qana]], Lebanon. The exact location [[Marriage at Cana|disputed]]]]\n[[File:Vineyards-chateau-ksara-lebanese-winery-wine.jpg|thumb|A Lebanese vineyard in the [[Beqaa Valley]]]]\n[[File:Roman-grotto-Chateau-Ksara-winery-beqaa-wine-Lebanon.jpg|thumb|Roman [[Ch\u00e2teau Ksara]] winery in Beqaa ]]\n\nLebanon is among the oldest sites of wine production in the world.<ref>McGovern, Patrick E. 2003. Ancient wine: the search for the origins of viniculture. Princeton University Press</ref> The Phoenicians of its coastal strip were instrumental in spreading wine and viticulture throughout the Mediterranean in ancient times. Lebanons Beqaa Valley contains for than 30 vineyards, including the renowned [[Kefraya]], [[Ksara]] and [[Ch\u00e2teau Musar]] labels.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Estreicher|first=Stefan K.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hCzUiYsGNwkC&pg=PA15&dq=lebanese+wine+phoenician&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiu-MziycXoAhVFtnEKHXKLCEsQ6AEINDAB#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20wine%20phoenician&f=false|title=Wine: From Neolithic Times to the 21st Century|date=2006|publisher=Algora Publishing|isbn=978-0-87586-477-8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Doyle|first=Paul|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0pt5DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA102&dq=lebanese+wine+for+sale&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDh6SjysXoAhWVURUIHfBzAZYQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20wine%20for%20sale&f=false|title=Lebanon|date=2016|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|year=|isbn=978-1-84162-558-4|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Wine Name\n| '''Date of Production'''\n| '''Origin'''\n| '''Founder'''\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Faqra<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vinileb.com/wineries/chateau-fakra.html|title=vinileb.com Chateau Fakra :: Online Wine cellar :: Lebanese Wine Shopping|website=vinileb.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| 1985\n| Fakra\n| Carlos Guillermo Adem\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau H\u00e9ritage<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chateauheritage.com/|title=Lebanese Wine Chateau Heritage Lebanon Wine|website=chateauheritage.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| 1888\n| [[Qabb Ilyas]]\n| Touma Family (la Famille Touma)\n|-\n\n! [[Ch\u00e2teau Kefraya]]\n| 1951\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Khoury<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chateaukhoury.com/|title=Welcome to our online shop|website=chateaukhoury.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n![[Ch\u00e2teau Marsyas]]\n| 2007\n| Beqaa Valley\n| Johnny R.Saad\u00e9 family\n|-\n! [[Ch\u00e2teau Musar]]\n| 1930\n| [[Beqaa Valley]]\n| Gaston Hochar\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Nakad in Jdita<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chateaunakad.com/|title=Chateau Nakad|website=chateaunakad.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N