afer Chaoui\n|-\n![[Massaya]]\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Nabise Mont Liban<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pictet|first=Fran\u00e7ois Jules|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.8425|title=Description de quelques poissons fossiles du Mont Liban / par F.-J. Pictet.|date=1850|publisher=impr. de Jules-Guillaume Fick,|location=G\u00e9n\u00e8ve :}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Terre Joie [http://www.terrejoie.com/]\n|    2011\n|    [[West Beqaa]]\n|    [[Joe Saade]]\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Lebanon|Food}}\n* [[Arab cuisine]]\n* [[Levantine cuisine]]\n* [[Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n* [[Mediterranean cuisine]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.recettelibanaise.com/ Lebanese Cuisine recipes]\n\n{{sisterlinks|Lebanon}}\n\n{{Asian topic|| cuisine}}\n{{Middle East topic |title=[[Middle Eastern cuisine]] |prefix=Cuisine of}}\n{{Mediterranean cuisine}}\n{{Cuisine}}\n\n{{use dmy dates|date=December 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lebanese Cuisine}}\n[[Category:Lebanese cuisine| ]]\n[[Category:Arab cuisine]]\n[[Category:Levantine cuisine]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n\n[[ar:\u0645\u0637\u0628\u062e \u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a]]\n[[de:Libanesische K\u00fcche]]\n[[es:Gastronom\u00eda del L\u00edbano]]\n[[fr:Cuisine libanaise]]\n[[ko:\ub808\ubc14\ub17c \uc694\ub9ac]]\n[[it:Cucina libanese]]\n[[nl:Libanese keuken]]\n[[ja:\u30ec\u30d0\u30ce\u30f3\u6599\u7406]]\n[[pt:Culin\u00e1ria do L\u00edbano]]\n[[ru:\u041b\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0443\u0445\u043d\u044f]]\n[[sv:Libanesiska k\u00f6ket]]\n[[tl:Lutuing Libanes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Culinary traditions of Lebanon}}\n[[File:Restauranthouder bij zijn shoarma spit, Bestanddeelnr 255-6509.jpg|thumb|A restaurateur with his shawarma [[Rotisserie|spit]], taken in [[Beirut]], Lebanon (1950)]]\n[[File:Mixed Plate (3186676853).jpg|thumb|Notable Lebanese dishes: [[Hummus]], [[Falafel]], [[Baba Ghanoush|Baba ghanoush]], [[Tabbouleh]], [[Shawarma]], [[Kafta]] and [[Kibbeh]]  ]]\n\n'''Lebanese cuisine''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0637\u0628\u062e \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a}}) is the culinary traditions and practices originating from [[Lebanon]]. It includes an abundance of [[whole grain]]s, [[fruit]]s, [[vegetable]]s, [[starches]], fresh [[Fish (food)|fish]] and [[seafood]]; animal fats are consumed sparingly. [[Poultry]] is eaten more often than [[red meat]], and when red meat is eaten, it is usually [[lamb and mutton|lamb]] on the coastal regions, and [[goat meat]] in the mountain regions. It also includes copious amounts of [[garlic]] and [[olive oil]], often seasoned by [[lemon juice]]. Chickpeas and parsley are also staples of the Lebanese diet.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheehan|first=Sean|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BrEG42oO2fgC&q=lebanese+chickpeas&dq=lebanese+chickpeas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi25K-9xsXoAhU7ThUIHffIAPgQ6AEIwgEwEg|title=Lebanon|date=1996-09|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-0283-1|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWell known savoury dishes include [[baba ghanouj]], a dip made of char-grilled [[eggplant]]; [[falafel]], small deep-fried patties made of highly spiced ground [[chickpeas]], fava beans, or a combination of the two; and [[shawarma]], a sandwich with marinated meat skewered and cooked on large rods. An important component of many Lebanese meals is [[hummus]], a dip or spread made of blended [[chickpeas]], sesame [[tahini]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]], typically eaten with pita bread.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kayyali|first=Randa A.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w2rc0RI7EqYC&pg=PA84&dq=lebanese+cuisine&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC3vXtxsXoAhWtShUIHR8TDZsQ6AEIrwMwMQ#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20cuisine&f=false|title=The Arab Americans|date=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-33219-7|language=en}}</ref> A well known dessert is [[baklava]], which is made of layered filo pastry filled with [[nut (fruit)|nuts]] and steeped in date syrup or honey. Some desserts are specifically prepared on special occasions: the ''[[meghli]]'', for instance, is served to celebrate a newborn baby in the family.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gall|first=Timothy L.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZLhZAAAAYAAJ&q=meghli+lebanon&dq=meghli+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwio5J2yr8LoAhVzQUEAHaKJC9sQ6AEITjAE|title=Worldmark Encyclopedia of Cultures and Daily Life|last2=Hobby|first2=Jeneen|date=2009|publisher=Gale|isbn=978-1-4144-4892-3|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Mouzawak|first=Kamal|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2P76CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT155&dq=meghli+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjoury1x8XoAhUESRUIHTjRAHgQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=meghli%20lebanon&f=false|title=Lebanese Home Cooking: Simple, Delicious, Mostly Vegetarian Recipes from the Founder of Beirut's Souk El Tayeb Market|date=2015-09-15|publisher=Quarry Books|isbn=978-1-63159-037-5|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Arak (distilled beverage)|Arak]], an anise-flavored liqueur, is the Lebanese national drink and usually served with a traditional convivial Lebanese meal. Another historic and traditional drink is [[Lebanese wine]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zurayk|first=Rami|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3lk-AQAAIAAJ&q=lebanese+arak&dq=lebanese+arak&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwip8d7Ex8XoAhU6UhUIHYpiAioQ6AEIVzAG|title=From \u02bbAkk\u0101r to \u02bbAmel: Lebanon's slow food trail : places, products and producers from Lebanon|last2=Rahman|first2=Sami Abdul|date=2008|publisher=Slow Food Beirut|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kuntz|first=Blair|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b5ptAAAAMAAJ&q=lebanese+wine&dq=lebanese+wine&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHlb3Vx8XoAhWCqHEKHVkMBQEQ6AEIlgEwDg|title=Lebanon: an insider's guide|date=2000|publisher=Prana Publishers|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Caption- Boys baking bread, Sidon orphanage. (9293979201).jpg|alt=|[[Sidonians]] baking bread in a [[Sidon|Saida]] orphanage (1919-1920)|thumb]]\nLebanese cuisine is an ancient one and part of the cuisine of the [[Levantine cuisine|Levant]]. Many dishes in Lebanese cuisine can be traced back thousands of years to eras of [[Ancient Rome|Roman]], [[Ancient Egypt]]ian, [[Phoenicia under Babylonian rule|Babylonian]], [[Phoenicia under Assyrian rule|Assyrian]], [[Hittites|Hittite]] and [[Phoenicia]]n rule.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mDnQwCJXUowC&q=babylonian+lebanon&dq=babylonian+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjfhdL4x8XoAhVKShUIHd_KCCEQ6AEIzQEwFA|title=Lebanon a country study|date=1989|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, Lebanese cuisine was influenced by the different foreign civilizations that held power. From 1516 to 1918, the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]] controlled Lebanon and introduced a variety of foods that have become staples in the Lebanese diet, such as cooking with [[lamb and mutton|lamb]]. After the Ottomans were defeated in [[World War I]] (1914\u20131918), [[France]] took control of Lebanon until 1943, when the country achieved its independence. The [[France|French]] introduced foods such as [[Flan (pie)|flan]], a [[caramel custard]] dessert dating back to the 16th century AD, [[eclairs]], [[french fries]] and [[croissant]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YEcLaAEACAAJ&dq=history+of+lebanese+food&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjlh_218_zQAhXMTSYKHRHfB9kQ6AEIGjAA|title=The Culinary Heritage of Lebanon|last=Choueiri|first=Ramzi N.|date=2002-01-01|publisher=Ramzi Choueiri|isbn=9789953007533|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Lebanese diaspora]] who live worldwide have introduced new foods, spices and culinary practices into Lebanese cuisine, keeping the cuisine innovative and renowned both beyond and within its borders.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hannam|first=Kevin|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cHTDCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA136&dq=lebanese+food+worldwide&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjJlerR1MLoAhVIKuwKHYm0AbEQ6AEIPzAD#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20food%20worldwide&f=false|title=Event Mobilities: Politics, place and performance|last2=Mostafanezhad|first2=Mary|last3=Rickly|first3=Jillian|date=2016-03-17|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-45047-4|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\n\nMost often foods are grilled, baked or saut\u00e9ed in olive oil; butter or cream is rarely used other than in a few desserts. Vegetables are often eaten raw, pickled, or cooked. Like most Mediterranean countries, much of what the Lebanese eat is dictated by the seasons and what is available. Lebanese cuisine also varies by region. South Lebanon is famous for its Kibbe, the Bekaa Valley for its meat pastries (such as [[Sfiha]]), and north Lebanon and Saida (Sidon) for its sweets.  \n{{multiple image\n| perrow = 2\n| total_width = 300\n| image1 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6517.jpg\n| image2 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6520.jpg\n| image3 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6518.jpg\n| image4 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6519.jpg\n| footer = Typical Lebanese dining, with [[mezze]] and wine, taken in a restaurant in Beirut, Lebanon (1950)\n| align = \n| direction = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| caption2 = \n}}\n\nIn [[Lebanon]], very rarely are drinks served without being accompanied by food. Similar to the [[tapas]] of [[Spain]], ''mezeluri'' of [[Romania]] and aperitivo of [[Italy]], ''[[mezze]]'' is an array of small dishes placed before the guests creating an array of colors, flavors, textures and aromas.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Walker|first=Harlan|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GsNyprRS7EIC&pg=PA268&dq=history+of+mezze&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj_iL_VyMXoAhUCUxUIHQYaAicQ6AEIPzAD#v=onepage&q=history%20of%20mezze&f=false|title=The Meal: Proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery, 2001|date=2002|publisher=Oxford Symposium|isbn=978-1-903018-24-8|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Cavendish\">{{Cite book|last=Cavendish|first=Marshall|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j894miuOqc4C&pg=PA979&dq=lebanese+mezze&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyhrSMsMLoAhUTecAKHaCEAWwQ6AEIUDAF#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20mezze&f=false|title=World and Its Peoples|date=September 2006|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-7571-2|language=en}}</ref> This style of serving food is less a part of family life than it is of entertaining and caf\u00e9s. Mezze may be as simple as raw or [[pickled vegetables]], [[hummus]], [[baba ghanouj]] and bread, or it may become an entire meal consisting of grilled marinated [[seafood]], skewered meats, a variety of cooked and raw salads and an arrangement of desserts. Family cuisine offers also a range of dishes, such as stews (or yakhneh), which can be cooked in many forms depending on the ingredients used and are usually served with [[meat]] and rice vermicelli. [[Pita]] bread is a [[staple food|staple]] of every Lebanese meal, and can be used in place of a fork.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cavendish|first=Marshall|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j894miuOqc4C&pg=PA979&dq=lebanese+mezze&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSspGhyMXoAhXSURUIHeb4Bg8Q6AEIUDAF#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20mezze&f=false|title=World and Its Peoples|date=2006|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|year=|isbn=978-0-7614-7571-2|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlthough simple fresh fruits are often served towards the end of a Lebanese meal, there is also [[dessert]], such as [[baklava]] and [[coffee]]. Although baklava is the most internationally known dessert, there is a great variety of Lebanese desserts.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hamadeh|first=Mona|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R0qWBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA211&dq=lebanese+desserts&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj7npbzyMXoAhVaURUIHU4NBv4Q6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20desserts&f=false|title=A Lebanese Feast of Vegetables, Pulses, Herbs and Spices|date=2015-08-06|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84528-580-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA typical ''[[mezze]]'' will consist of an elaborate variety of thirty hot and cold dishes and may include:\n\n* Salads such as [[tabbouleh]] and [[fattoush]], together with dip such as [[hummus]], [[baba ghanoush]] or ''moutabal'', and [[kebbeh]],\n* Some patties such as the [[sambusac]],\n*[[Stuffed grape leaves]] and pickles,\n* Roasted nuts, olives and vegetables; served with condiments like [[toum]] and [[Tarator|taratour]], ideal for spread on [[sfiha]].<ref name=\"Cavendish\"/><ref>{{Cite book|last=Rombauer|first=Irma S.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jcq2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&dq=mezze+nuts&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4oKvIycXoAhXOQxUIHZi-DWMQ6AEIQTAD#v=onepage&q=mezze%20nuts&f=false|title=Joy of Cooking: 2019 Edition Fully Revised and Updated|last2=Becker|first2=Marion Rombauer|last3=Becker|first3=Ethan|last4=Becker|first4=John|last5=Scott|first5=Megan|date=2019-11-12|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-5011-6971-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe assortments of dishes forming the mezze are generally consumed in small bites using a piece of Lebanese bread ([[khubz]], [[pita]]) or a fork. As a family, it is made up of three or four dishes, but in the restaurant, the mezze can range from twenty to sixty dishes, as the varient combinations and dishes involved are plenty.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jousiffe|first=Ann|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q7IUAQAAIAAJ&q=lebanese+mezze+dishes&dq=lebanese+mezze+dishes&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiO2oO_zcXoAhXWQRUIHYFtCFQQ6AEIeTAK|title=Lebanon|date=1998|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-0-86442-350-4|language=en}}</ref><gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"200\" heights=\"170\" mode=\"packed-overlay\" caption=\"''A selection of well-known dishes within the Lebanese cuisine:''\">\nFile:Palestinianbreakfastfalafel.jpg|[[Falafel]], with hummus, [[Pita]] and various vegetables\nFile:Byblos Harbour, Millwall, London (3639283205).jpg|From left to right: [[Hummus]], [[Ful medames]] (fava bean stew), [[Batata harra]] (spicy potatoes) and [[Moussaka]]\nFile:Kibbeh Nayyeh.jpg|[[Kibbeh nayyeh]]\nFile:Petit assortiment de nourriture libanaise (Lyon, 2017).jpg|Assortment of nutritious Lebanese food, served in Lyon, [[France]]\nFile:Sheikhmahshe.JPG|Sheikh Mahshi served with rice\nFile:Mixedlebanesefood.JPG|Clockwise from bottom right: [[Kafta]] (grilled spiced ground meat), [[Balila (dish)|Balila]] (boiled chickpeas in lemon and garlic dressing), [[Tabbouleh]] and [[Mashawi]] (barbecued spiced meat)\nFile:Tabbouleh2.JPG|Lebanese [[Tabbouleh]] served with lettuce\nFile:Sayadiyah Fish.jpg|Sayadieh Samak (baked fish with rice)\n</gallery>\n\n==Dishes and ingredients==\n[[File:Baklava - Turkish special, 80-ply.JPEG|thumb|Mediterranean-style baklava]]\n[[File:Fatethomos.JPG|thumb|Lebanese Fateh b'hummus|alt=]]\n[[File:Ful medames (arabic meal).jpg|thumb|Fava bean stew, or [[Ful medames]] (Lebanese Style)]]\n[[File:Ftayerbelefet.JPG|thumb|Ftayer be sbenigj ([[spinach|spin]][[spinach|ach]] [[turnover (food)|turnovers]])]]\n[[File:Fattoush.JPG|alt=|thumb|[[Fattoush]]]]\n[[File:Sfiha2.jpg|thumb|[[Sfiha]], a pie-like dish from the Lebanese town of [[Baalbek]]]]\n\n* [[Ackawi cheese|Ackawi]] - white cheese salty or not depending on choice.\n* [[Halloum cheese|Halloum]] - white cheese salty, can be grilled.\n* [[Baba ghanouj]] - char-grilled ''aubergine'' ([[eggplant]]), [[tahina]], [[olive oil]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]] puree\u2014served as a dip.\n* [[Batata harra]] - spicy cube potatoes fried.\n* [[Baklava]] - a dessert of layered pastry filled with [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s and steeped in Attar syrup ([[Orange (fruit)|orange]] or rose water and [[sugar]]), usually cut in a triangular or diamond shape that originates in Lebanon,   it is a rich, sweet pastry made of layers of filo pastry filled with chopped nuts and sweetened with syrup or honey .\n* [[Roasting|Roasted]] [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]] - a mix of more than 20 kinds and flavors of [[kernels]], mostly dry roasted.\n* [[Balila]] - known as [[cumin]] [[chickpeas]].\n* [[Barout del batata]] - spicy lamb served with potatoes.\n* [[Chawarma lahmeh]] -  grilled meat with parsley, onion and tarator (served as a sandwich or a plat.)\n* [[Chawarma djeij]] -  grilled poultry with toum (garlic) and lettuce (served as a sandwich or a plat.)\n* [[Chich Taouk]] - grilled chicken marinated with garlic lemon and various oriental spices (cinnamon, cumin...)\n* [[Daoud Bacha]] - meatballs with tomato sauce.\n* [[Djaj Mechwi]] - grilled chicken on bbq marinated with a garlic lemon sauce.\n* [[Fattoush]] - 'peasant' salad of toasted pita bread, [[cucumbers]], [[tomatoes]], [[chickweed]], and [[Mentha|mint]].\n* [[Falafel]] - small deep-fried patties made of highly-spiced ground [[chickpeas]].\n* [[Fried cauliflower]] - served with tarator sauce.\n* [[Fried eggplant]]\n* [[Fatteh]] - [[chickpeas]], [[yogurt]], [[minced meat]], spices and grilled Lebanese pita cut in triangle.\n* [[Ful medames|Fuul]] (''[[vicia faba]]'') slow cooked mash of brown [[beans]] and red [[lentils]] dressed with [[lemon]], [[olive oil]] and [[cumin]].\n* [[Halva]] - sesame paste sweet, usually made in a slab and studded with [[fruit]] and [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s.\n* [[Hummus]] - dip or spread made of blended [[chickpeas]], sesame [[tahini]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]], and typically eaten with pita bread.\n* [[Hummus ras aasfour]] - dip made of blended [[chickpeas]], sesame [[tahini]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]], with meat on top, eaten with pita bread.\n* [[Jwenih]] - chicken wings cooked with coriander, garlic and lemon, served as mezze.\n* [[Kanafeh|Kunafi]] - either shoelace pastry dessert stuffed with sweet [[white cheese]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2020}}, [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s and [[syrup]], or more commonly the version with semolina pastry served on a [[sesame seed]] bun with sweet sugar syrup (very popular for breakfast) made with \" angel hair\" butter and pistachios or nuts. Generally these can be found in sweet shops, as well as bigger bakeries.\n* [[Kibbeh]] - the national dish, mainly stuffed, can be made in different forms including fried, uncooked, and cooked with [[yogurt]].\n* [[Kibbeh nayyeh]] - raw kibbeh eaten like [[steak]] tartar.\n* [[Kofta]] - fingers, stars or a flat cake of [[Ground meat|minced meat]] and [[spices]] that can be baked or charcoal-grilled on skewers.\n* [[Kousa Mahshi]]- stuffed [[zucchini]], many varieties are used.\n* [[Kubideh]] - served with ''[[pivaz]]'' (a mix of minced [[parsley]], [[onions]], ground [[cumin]] and [[sumac]]).\n* [[Labneh]]- strained yogurt, spreadable and garnished with good olive oil and [[sea salt]].\n* [[Labneh we toum]] - strained yogurt mixed with garlic, spreadable and garnished with good olive oil and [[sea salt]].\n* [[Ladies' fingers|Znood Es-sett]] - filo pastry cigars with various fillings.\n* [[Sfiha|Lahm bil aj\u0129n]] - a pastry covered with [[Ground meat|minced meat]], [[onions]], and [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]].\n* [[Ma'amoul]] -  cake made from semolina with [[date (fruit)|date]], [[pistachio]] or [[walnut]] filled cookies shaped in a wooden mould called a ''tabi'' made specially for Christian (traditionally Eastern) and Muslim holidays (such as [[Ramadan]]).\n* [[Mfaraket Koussa]] spicy zucchini.\n* [[Manakousheh zaatar]] thyme pizza usually served for breakfast.\n* [[Manakousheh jebneh]] only cheese Lebanese pizza usually served for breakfast.\n* [[Lahm bi ajain]] (also called mankhoucheh lahmeh) - minced meat with tomatoes and onion, usually served with yogurt drink\n* [[Makdous]] - stuffed eggplant in olive oil.\n* [[Manaeesh]] - mini pizzas that are made in any number of local bakeries or Furns (Furn Assalam, Ain El Hilwe, Saida), traditionally garnished with [[cheese]], [[Za'atar]], spicy diced tomatoes, [[kashk]] in its Lebanese version, or minced meat and onions. Some bakeries allow you to bring your own toppings and build your own or buy the ones they sell there. Breakfast, lunch and dinner.\n* [[Mujaddara]] (''imjaddarra'') - cooked [[lentils]] together with [[wheat]] or [[rice]], garnished with onions that have been 'sauteed' (lightly cooked in vegetable oil).\n* [[Mulukhiyah]] - A stew with mallow leaves, [[chicken]], [[beef]], and in the Lebanese fashion, topped with raw chopped onions, and [[vinegar]] over rice. It sometimes has toasted pita chips under the rice.\n* [[Mutabbel]] - made from eggplant.\n* [[Pastirma]] - cured, seasoned dried beef.[[File:Kibbetbatata.JPG|thumb|Kibbet batata ([[potato]] [[kibbeh]])]]\n* [[Qawarma]] - chopped lamb, salted and kept in the grease of the animal.\n* [[Samkeh Harra]] - grilled [[fish]] that has been marinated with [[Chili pepper|chili]], [[citrus]], and [[cilantro]]\n* [[Shanklish]] - aged cheese balls.\n* [[Shawarma]] - marinated meat (either [[chicken]] or [[lamb and mutton|lamb]]) that is skewered on big rods and cooked slowly, then shaved and placed in a 10&nbsp;inch pita roll with [[pickling|pickles]], [[tomatoes]], and other tangy condiments.\n* [[Shish taouk]]- grilled chicken skewers that utilize only white meat, marinated in olive oil, lemon, parsley, and sumac.\n* [[Siyyadiyeh]] - delicately spiced fish served on a bed of rice. Fish cooked in [[saffron]] and served on rice with [[onions]], [[sumac]], and a [[tahini]] sauce (the most important part of the dish) originated in Saida (sidon).\n* [[Sfiha]] - a dish from the Lebanese town of [[Baalbek]].\n* [[Tabbouleh]] - diced parsley salad with [[burghul]], [[tomato]] and [[Mentha|mint]].\n* [[Tahini]] - sesame paste.\n* [[Toum]] - garlic sauce.\n* [[Dolma|Wara' Enab]] (''dolma'') - stuffed grape leaves.\n* [[Za'atar]] - dried [[thyme]] and sumac that can differ from region to region and from family to family. Most are made in house, but can be bought at Lebanese larders.\n* Lebanese Spice Blend - a mixture of equal parts of [[allspice]], [[black pepper]], [[cinnamon]], [[cloves]], [[fenugreek]], [[nutmeg]] and [[ginger]]. It is commonly used to flavor many Lebanese dishes.\n\n== Sweets ==\n[[File:Middle eastern sweets.jpg|alt=|thumb|Selection of Lebanese sweets made in S\u00e3o Paulo, [[Brazil]], sold by one of the many Lebanese restaurants within the Brazilian [[Lebanese diaspora]]|left]]\n[[File:Atayebasafeeri.JPG|thumb|Modern presentation of Lebanese dessert ''[[qatayef]] asafiri'' |alt=]]\nThe modern form of Lebanese desserts have been influenced by [[Ottoman cuisine]] and share many similarties with other Levantine countries, including [[muhallebi]], a milk [[pudding]] made with rice, milk and sugar. Like many other Lebanese desserts it is sweetened with ''[[atar]]'' syrup and served with a garnish of assorted nuts.<ref name=\"sweets\">{{cite book |last1=Roufs |first1=Timothy G. |last2=Roufs |first2=Kathleen Smyth |title=Sweet Treats Around the World |pages=179\u2013183}}</ref>\n\n''[[Barazeh]]'', also found in [[Syrian cuisine]], are cookies with a light and crumbly texture; one size is decorated with sesame seeds and the other [[pistachio]]. ''[[Ma'amoul]]'' are crumbly cookies filled with pistachio, walnuts or [[Dates (fruit)|dates]]. [[Lebanese Christians]] serve ''ma'amoul'' with ''atar'' syrup for Easter, as well as a cake flavored with [[anise]] and ''[[mahlab]]''.<ref name=\"sweets\" />[[File:Lebanon - Baklava - Karabij - Eclair (2318962553).jpg|thumb|Mix of Lebanese desserts incuding [[Baklava]], [[\u00c9clair]], Karabij and others]]\n\nPastry shops in Tripoli offer the common ''[[baklava]]'' along with other local specialty pastries like ''halawet al jibn'', filled with sweetened cheese and topped with ''atar'', pistachios, [[clotted cream]] (''ashta'') and [[rose jam]]. ''Znoud al-sit'', a syrup-soaked rolled pastry filled with clotted cream and garnished in typical fashion with nuts, orange peels and [[Dates (fruit)|dates]] to the 19th century.<ref name=\"sweets\" />\n\n[[Semolina]] is used in the preparation of several Lebanese desserts like the pistachio-filled cookie ''[[karabeej|karabij]]'' (or aleppo cookies), flavored with ''[[mahlab]]'' and cinnamon, and served with ''[[natef]]'', a topping similar to [[meringue]]. ''[[Mafroukeh]]'' is a semolina dough layered with caramel and butter, soaked in ''atar'' and served with clotted cream and assorted nuts. It can also be used to make cakes like ''[[basbousa|nammoura]]''.<ref name=sweets/>\n\nDesserts include pastries such as [[Aish as-Saraya]], [[Qatayef]], [[Basbousa]], [[Harees]], [[Kanafeh]], [[baklava]], [[Ka'ak]], [[Sfouf]] and [[Maamoul]]. Lebanese [[ice cream]] is popular with its oriental flavors, including [[Qamar al-Din|Amar al-Din]] made from dried apricots (can also be eaten as a snack); fresh fruits, and pistachio. Lebanese roasted [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]] with a variety of different mixes and flavours can be eaten before, during and after meals.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hamadeh|first=Mona|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R0qWBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA211&dq=lebanese+desserts&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj7npbzyMXoAhVaURUIHU4NBv4Q6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20desserts&f=false|title=A Lebanese Feast of Vegetables, Pulses, Herbs and Spices|date=2015-08-06|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84528-580-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== By region ==\n{{Culture of region\n| name          = Culture of Lebanon\n| region        = Lebanon\n| image         = Flag-map of Lebanon.svg\n| imagesize     = 150\n| cuisoverride  = Lebanese cuisine\n}}\nThese recipes are attributed to these regions in Lebanon, although you find them now as main dishes at most Lebanese homes across the country with local variations.\n\n*Ain-Zibdeh: Hareeseh (wheat and beef)\n*[[Ajaltoun]]: Maakroun bi Thineh (Pastry boiled to which is added lemon and Thineh)\n*[[Aley]]: Tabbouleh bi Dehn (cooked tabouleh with lentils with beef ghee)\n*[[Baalbek]]: Safiha Baalbakieh (meat-stuffed puff pastry)\n*Baino: Kebbe and Lahme bil-khal (meat mixed with crushed wheat and meat soaked in vinegar)\n*[[Baskinta]]: Makhlouta (meat, rice, and nuts)\n*[[Beirut]]: Samkeh Harra and Akhtabout (spicy fish and octopus), Roastuts\n*[[Beit Chabab]]: Riz bi-Djaj (chicken with rice)\n*[[Beit Mery]]: Kebbe Lakteen (pumpkin-flavoured meat)\n*[[Beiteddine]]: Kafta Bithine (spiced meat with sesame concentrate)\n*[[Broummana]]: Deleh Mehshi (stuffed rib cage of lamb)\n*[[Bsharri]]: Koussa bil-Laban (meat and rice-stuffed zucchini cooked in yoghurt)\n*[[Dhour El Choueir]]: [[Shishbarak|Shish Barak]] (dough balls stuffed with ground beef and cooked in yoghurt)\n*[[Douma, Lebanon|Douma]]: Laban Immo (cooked yoghurt and lamb with rice)\n*[[Ehden]]: Kebbe Zghartweih (oven-cooked meat and crushed wheat blend)\n*[[El-Koura|El Koura]]: Abu Shoushe (taro and lentils stew)\n* Ferzol: [[Freekeh|Freikeh]] (cooked wheat with meat)\n*[[Hammana]]: Fasoulya Hammanieh (kidney bean stew)\n* Hrajel: Zaatar baladi (Thym with sesame, salt and olive oil)\n* Ihmej: Ghameh (stuffed cow intestines)\n*[[Jbeil]]: Koussa and Wark Inab bil-Kastaletah (stuffed zucchini, grape vines and steak)\n* Kifar meshki: Kebbe bil-Kishk (meat mixed with wheat and yoghurt)\n*[[Marjayoun]]: Vine leaves with squash and grilled chicken\n*[[Nabatieh]]: [[Sfiha]] (open-faced [[meat pie]]s made with ground [[mutton]]\n*[[Al-Qalamoun|Qalamoun]]: Fresh Carrot juice with ice cream inside\n*[[Ras el-Matn|Ras El Matn]]: Fatet (yoghurt, fried bread and nuts)\n* Rashana: Mjadrat Fasoulya (lentils and kidney beans)\n*[[Rashaya|Rashaya Al Wadi]]: Kebbe Heeleh (meatballs)\n* Saghbeen and [[Machghara]]: Zinkoul bil-Laban (meat filled pastry and yoghurt)\n*[[Shouf]]: Fatet Batinjan (yoghurt, fried bread and aubergine) and [[mate (beverage)|mate]]\n*[[Sidon]]: Riz bil-Foul (Rice and fava beans)\n*[[Tripoli, Lebanon]]: Mjadrah and Fattoush (crushed lentils and salad)\n*[[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]: Saiyadit al-Samak (rice and fish)\n*[[Zahl\u00e9]]: Kebbe Zahleweieh (meat and crushed wheat blend)\n\n== Beverages ==\n\n*[[Arabic coffee]]\n*[[Almaza Beer|Beer]], alcoholic beverage{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| total_width = 620\n| image_style = border:none;\n| image1 = Arabic coffee.jpg\n| alt1 = Arabic coffee\n| caption1 = [[Arabic coffee]]\n| image2 = Arak with water and ice.jpg\n| alt2 = Arak with water and ice\n| caption2 = [[Arak (drink)|Arak]] with water and ice\n| image3 = Jallab.jpg\n| alt3 = Jallab\n| caption3 = [[Jallab]], made from [[carob]], [[Date palm|dates]], grape [[molasses]] and [[rose water]]\n| image4 = Coffee Syria 2.jpg\n| alt4 = Black Coffee\n| caption4 = Lebanese style black coffee\n}}\n*[[Arak (liqueur)|Arak]], alcoholic beverage\n*[[Ayran]], yogurt\n*[[Coffee|Black coffee]]\n*[[Ceratonia siliqua|Le caroubier]], non-alcoholic beverage made from carob\n*[[Jallab]], sweet drink\n*[[Lebanese wine]], alcoholic beverage\n*[[Mate (beverage)|Mate]] in [[Shouf]] and [[Aley]]\n*[[Turkish coffee]]\n\n== Lebanese wine ==\n{{See also|Lebanese wine|Phoenicians and wine}}\n[[File:Grape presses and jars from the wedding of Qana.jpg|thumb|Grape presses and jars from the [[Marriage at Cana]], the first miracle attributed to [[Jesus]], Located in [[Qana]], Lebanon. The exact location [[Marriage at Cana|disputed]]]]\n[[File:Vineyards-chateau-ksara-lebanese-winery-wine.jpg|thumb|A Lebanese vineyard in the [[Beqaa Valley]]]]\n[[File:Roman-grotto-Chateau-Ksara-winery-beqaa-wine-Lebanon.jpg|thumb|Roman [[Ch\u00e2teau Ksara]] winery in Beqaa ]]\n\nLebanon is among the oldest sites of wine production in the world.<ref>McGovern, Patrick E. 2003. Ancient wine: the search for the origins of viniculture. Princeton University Press</ref> The Phoenicians of its coastal strip were instrumental in spreading wine and viticulture throughout the Mediterranean in ancient times. Lebanons Beqaa Valley contains for than 30 vineyards, including the renowned [[Kefraya]], [[Ksara]] and [[Ch\u00e2teau Musar]] labels.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Estreicher|first=Stefan K.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hCzUiYsGNwkC&pg=PA15&dq=lebanese+wine+phoenician&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiu-MziycXoAhVFtnEKHXKLCEsQ6AEINDAB#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20wine%20phoenician&f=false|title=Wine: From Neolithic Times to the 21st Century|date=2006|publisher=Algora Publishing|isbn=978-0-87586-477-8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Doyle|first=Paul|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0pt5DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA102&dq=lebanese+wine+for+sale&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDh6SjysXoAhWVURUIHfBzAZYQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20wine%20for%20sale&f=false|title=Lebanon|date=2016|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|year=|isbn=978-1-84162-558-4|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Wine Name\n| '''Date of Production'''\n| '''Origin'''\n| '''Founder'''\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Faqra<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vinileb.com/wineries/chateau-fakra.html|title=vinileb.com Chateau Fakra :: Online Wine cellar :: Lebanese Wine Shopping|website=vinileb.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| 1985\n| Fakra\n| Carlos Guillermo Adem\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau H\u00e9ritage<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chateauheritage.com/|title=Lebanese Wine Chateau Heritage Lebanon Wine|website=chateauheritage.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| 1888\n| [[Qabb Ilyas]]\n| Touma Family (la Famille Touma)\n|-\n\n! [[Ch\u00e2teau Kefraya]]\n| 1951\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Khoury<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chateaukhoury.com/|title=Welcome to our online shop|website=chateaukhoury.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n![[Ch\u00e2teau Marsyas]]\n| 2007\n| Beqaa Valley\n| Johnny R.Saad\u00e9 family\n|-\n! [[Ch\u00e2teau Musar]]\n| 1930\n| [[Beqaa Valley]]\n| Gaston Hochar\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Nakad in Jdita<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chateaunakad.com/|title=Chateau Nakad|website=chateaunakad.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Qanafar<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chateauqanafar.com/|title=Ch\u00e2teau Qanafar|website=Ch\u00e2teau Qanafar|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| 2010\n| [[Beqaa Valley]]\n| Naim family\n|-\n! Couvent St. Sauveur\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! [http://www.domainedestourelles.com/ Domaine des Tourelles]\n|1868\n| [[Beqaa Valley]], Chtaura\n| Fran\u00e7ois-Eug\u00e8ne Brun\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2t