{"title_page": "Ashley Chin", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Ashley Chin\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = AshleyChinOctober2019.png\n| image_size       = 220px\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Ashley Chin (right) with Hope Ikpoku at the launch of his book ''Faith'' in October 2019.\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Ashley Anthony Chin\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1982|8|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| death_cause      = \n| resting_place    = \n| nationality      = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| other_names      = {{hlist|Muslim Belal|Smalls}}\n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Actor]]\n* [[Screenwriter]]\n* [[Rapping|Rapper]]\n* [[Spoken Word]]\n*[[Performance poetry|Performance Poet]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 1999\u2013present\n| employer         = \n| organization     = \n| agent            = \n| known_for        = \n| notable_works    = \n| style            =  \n| home_town        = \n| salary           = \n| net_worth        = \n| height           = <!--{{height|ft=5|in=9.5}}}}-->\n| weight           = <!--{{convert|76|kg|lb st|abbr=on}}}}-->\n| television       = \n| title            = \n| term             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| party            = \n| movement         = \n| opponents        = \n| boards           = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| children         = 1\n| parents          = <!--Andrea Ellis (mother)}}-->\n| relatives        = <!--Kareena Chin (sister)<br/>Richard Chin (brother)<br/>Brandon Chin (brother)}}-->\n| awards           = \n| module           = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| alias            = \n| origin           = <!--[[London]], [[England]]-->\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Islamic music|Islamic]]\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip-hop]]\n* [[Spoken word]]\n* [[Anasheed|Nasheed]]\n}}\n| occupation       = \n| instrument       = [[Singing|Vocals]]\n| years_active     = 2005\u2013present\n| label            = Halal Dawa Records\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Mecca2Medina]]|[[Poetic Pilgrimage]]|[[Suli Breaks]]|[[Lowkey]]}}\n| website          = <!--{{URL|http://www.muslimbelal.co.uk/}} dead link--> {{url|https://www.shahaadahproductions.com/}}\n| notable_instruments = \n}}\n| website          = \n| footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Ashley Belal Chin''' (born 21 August 1982), also known as '''Muslim Belal''', is an [[England|English]] [[actor]], [[screenwriter]], [[spoken word]] [[Performance poetry|performance]] [[poet]] and a [[Rapping|rapper]] of [[British Jamaican|Jamaican]] descent.\n\nHe began his acting career in the 1999 [[BBC Films|BBC film]] ''[[Storm Damage]]'' and his music career in 2005. He has acted in a number of stage productions including ''[[Gone Too Far!]]'' (2007). Chin came to prominence as a supporting role in the films ''[[Sket]]'' (2011) and ''[[Anuvahood]]'' (2011). He is perhaps best known for his role as Tyson in the film ''[[Victim (2011 film)|Victim]]'' (2011) and Michael in the award-winning short film ''[[The Boxer (2012 film)|The Boxer]]''. Chin also played the role of the antagonist, G-Money, in ''[[The Intent]]'' (2016), and reprised his role in the prequel ''[[The Intent 2: The Come Up]]'' (2018). He played the role of Isaac in the short film series ''[[The Essence (film)|The Essence]]'' (2019). Chin has also released a book titled ''Faith'' in October 2019 and states that the book is based on his journey from the streets to Islam. A film based on the book is set to be released in 2020 and Chin is set to write and direct the film.\n\nWith muic and poetry, Chin performs under his alias \"Muslim Belal\" and released his debut album ''[[Pray Hard]]'' in 2009. He released his second album ''[[The Transition (album)|The Transition]]'' in 2010. His third studio album ''[[My Sumaya]]'' was released in 2015. Chin's poetry combines spiritualism with social issues and his own personal history.<ref name=\"restlessbeings\">{{cite news |url=http://www.restlessbeings.org/events/human-writes|title=Human Writes \u2013 Events|publisher=Restless Beings|date=27 November 2010|accessdate=1 July 2012}} Muslim Belal</ref> He also works as a life coach and delivers workshops and talks at youth clubs, universities and events.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nChin was born in [[Gypsy Hill]], [[London]], [[England]].<ref name=\"tobeseen\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tobeseen.co.uk/jobs/Casting-for-Feature-Film-The-Chrysalis-?id=8654|title=Acting Jobs \u2013 Auditions \u2013 Casting Calls|publisher=To Be Seen|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"starnow\">{{cite web |url=http://www.starnow.co.uk/Casting-Calls/Actors-wanted/Feature-film/casting_for_film_the_chrysalis_directed_by_award_winning_sheila_nortley.htm|title=Casting for film The chrysalis directed by Award Winning Sheila Nortley-LDN|publisher=Star Now|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> His parents are from [[Jamaica]], he was named after his paternal grandfather who was [[China|Chinese]].<ref name=\"thedeenshow\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B0t9rQ-jmlg|title=Jamaican Musician accepts Islam|work=The Deen Show|publisher=[[Islam Channel]]|date=16 June 2011|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> He grew up with his mother, Andrea Ellis, and elder sister, Kareena Chin, in a [[South London]] council estate.<ref name=\"tmpost\">{{cite news |last=Lais|first=Hasnet|url=http://www.tmpost.com/?p=5739|title=Interview: Ashley Chin a.k.a. Muslim Bilal. \"Victim movie is released in cinemas nationwide today 22 June\"|work=The Muslim Post|date=22 June 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> He was brought up as a [[Christians|Christian]],<ref name=\"thedeenshow\"/> however spent his youth being involved in gang culture.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web |last=Louise|first=Maria|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0157717/bio|title=Ashley Chin \u2013 Biography|website=[[Internet Movie Database|IMDb]]|year=2009|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nChin achieved an A grade in [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] drama and left school at the age of 15.<ref name=\"tmpost\"/><ref name=\"taletela\">{{cite news |last=Pharoah|first=Samson|url=http://www.taletela.com/news/16966/interview-ashley-chin-talks-working-on-new-movie-victim|title=INTERVIEW: Ashley Chin Talks Working on New Movie 'Victim'|publisher=TaleTela|date=22 June 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> In 1999, Chin and his family moved to [[Thornton Heath]], [[Croydon]].\n\nChin had a talent for poetry, which he started developing from the age of 12.<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news|last=Hasnet|first=Lais|url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/10/10/faith-and-film-actor-ashley-chin%E2%80%99s-balancing-act/|title=Faith and film: Actor Ashley Chin\u2019s balancing act|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=10 October 2012|accessdate=1 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114094001/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/10/10/faith-and-film-actor-ashley-chin%E2%80%99s-balancing-act/|archive-date=14 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2001, he and a friend set up a music studio,<ref name=\"muslimyouthskills\">{{cite news|last=Tahir |first=Nadim |url=http://www.muslimyouthskills.co.uk/social-initiatives/connect/35-issue-5-july-2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203033850/http://www.muslimyouthskills.co.uk/social-initiatives/connect/35-issue-5-july-2009 |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 December 2013 |title=Exclusive interview with 'Muslim Belal'. A Multi-Skilled entertainer and Islamic Rap Artist and former member of the notorious South London Group known as 'SMS' |location=London |publisher=Tawheed Is Unity TV |date=5 July 2009 |accessdate=1 July 2012 }}</ref> for a band, where Chin used to play keyboards and different sound boards.<ref name=\"islamicgarden\">{{cite news |last=Cook|first=Selma|url=http://www.islamicgarden.com/bilalchin.html|title=Bilal Chin - South London Rapper Finds Islam|publisher=The Islamic Garden|date=18 October 2009|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> The former street gang<ref name=\"londonstreetgangs\">{{cite web |url=https://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/south-man-syndicate|title=South Man Syndicate (SMS)|publisher=londonstreetgangs.com|accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref> and musical collective was called SMS 'South Man Syndicate' (later known as South Muslim Soldiers),<ref name=\"tawheedisunity\">{{cite news|url=http://tawheedisunity.com/2012/01/28/muslim-belal-from-kuwait-and-beyond/|title=Muslim Belal \u2013 From Kuwait And Beyond|publisher=Tawheed Is Unity TV|date=28 January 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> and he was known at the time as Smalls.\n\n==Career==\n===1999\u20132006: ''Beginnings''===\nIn 1999, Chin began his acting career in the [[BBC Films|BBC film]] ''[[Storm Damage]]'' directed by [[Lennie James]].<ref name=\"screenonline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/441333/credits.html|title=Storm Damage (2000) Credits|website=[[Screenonline]]|date=23 January 2000|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> He then made his theatre debut as the role of Young Mal in [[Roy Williams (playwright)|Roy Williams']] ''Lift Off'' at the [[Royal Court Theatre]].<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news |last=Morley|first=Sheridan|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/03/style/03iht-lon.t.html|title=Tribute in 'Toast' : Men at Work:|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=3 March 1999|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> Chin converted to Islam in 2002, during this time he stepped away from his career to focus on his faith. Since his conversion to Islam, Chin has adopted the name Muslim Belal. In December 2005, under this [[stage name]], he performed at the inaugural [[Global Peace and Unity|Global Peace and Unity Event]] in the [[ExCeL London|ExCeL Exhibition Centre]] organised by [[Islam Channel]].<ref name=\"GPU05\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moftak.com/gu05/ |title=Global Peace & Unity Event 2005 |date=4 December 2005 |accessdate=1 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030045917/http://www.moftak.com/gu05/ |archivedate=30 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132009: ''Return to Acting and Pray Hard''===\nChin returned to acting in 2007, where he played Razer in [[Bola Agbaje]]'s [[Laurence Olivier]] award-winning play ''[[Gone Too Far!]]''.<ref name=\"flavourmag1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.flavourmag.co.uk/bola-agbaje-gone-too-far/|title=Bola Agbaje: Gone Too Far|publisher=Flavour Magazine|date=7 October 2008|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"thestage1\">{{cite news |last=Berkowitz|first=Gerald|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/15856/gone-too-far-|title=Gone Too Far!|newspaper=[[The Stage]]|date=7 February 2007|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> Laurence Olivier was impressed with Chin's performance that he made him reprise his role in 2008.<ref name=\"thestage3\">{{cite news |last=Smith|first=Alistair|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/21428/gone-too-far|title=Gone Too Far!|newspaper=[[The Stage]]|date=31 July 2008|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"musicomh\">{{cite news |first=Natasha |last=Tripney |url=http://www.musicomh.com/theatre/gone_0708.htm|title=Gone Too Far!|publisher=[[musicOMH]]|date=August 2008|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"hackneyempire\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hackneyempire.co.uk/?lid=469|title=Gone Too Far!|publisher=Hackney Empire|date=August 2008|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> He also played the role of Carl Wilkins in Roy Williams' ''There's Only One Wayne Matthews'' at the Polka Theatre.<ref name=\"thestage2\">{{cite news |last=Usher|first=Catherine|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/18454/theres-only-one-wayne-matthews|title=There's Only One Wayne Matthews!|newspaper=[[The Stage]]|date=8 October 2007|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"edfilmfest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edfilmfest.org.uk/industry/trailblazers/2010/ashley-chin|title=Ashley Chin|work=Trailblazer Profiles|publisher=Edinburgh International Film Festival|date=9 June 2010|accessdate=1 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201224137/http://www.edfilmfest.org.uk/industry/trailblazers/2010/ashley-chin|archive-date=1 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2007, he played the role of Seales in [[BBC Radio 4]]'s radio adaptation of [[E. R. Braithwaite]]'s novel ''[[To Sir, With Love (novel)|To Sir, With Love]]''.<ref name=\"thegbcc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thegbcc.info/Misc/w-dr/Braithwaite,%20E%20R.html|title=Braithwaite, E R|publisher=Global British Comedy Collaborative |date=27 December 2010|accessdate=1 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101152431/http://www.thegbcc.info/Misc/w-dr/Braithwaite,%20E%20R.html|archive-date=1 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"radiolistings\">{{cite web |url=http://www.radiolistings.co.uk/programmes/t/to/to_sir_with_love.html|title=To Sir With Love|publisher=Radio Listings|date=13 April 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> Chin also starred in a supporting role in the television series''[[The Bill]]'' in 2007.<ref name=\"thebill1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/the-bill/code-of-silence-1127511/cast/|title=The Bill Cast & Crew|work=Code of Silence: Season 23, Episode 62|publisher=[[TV.com]]|date=23 August 2007|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"thebill2\">{{cite web |url= http://www.itv.com/presscentre/thebill/week33/default.html|title= The Bill|work=Tombstone: Season 26, Episode 29|publisher=[[itv.com]]|date=17 August 2010|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> He also had supporting roles in''[[HolbyBlue]]'',<ref name=\"edfilmfest\"/> ''[[The Fixer (2008 TV series)|The Fixer]]'',<ref name=\"thefixer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/thefixer/s2ep1wk36/default.html|title=The Fixer|work=Season 2 Episode 1 Week 36|publisher=[[itv.com]]|date=19 August 2009|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> and ''[[Law & Order: UK]]'' during this time<ref name=\"lawandorder\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/law-and-order-uk/samaritan-1284005/cast/|title=Law & Order: UK Cast & Crew|work=Samaritan \u2013 Season 2, Episode 1|publisher=[[TV.com]]|date=1 November 2010|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, Chin performed at the [[Islam Expo]] in [[Olympia (London)|Olympia]], London.<ref name=\"islamexpo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.islamexpo.com/attractions.php?id=7&art=18|title=11\u201314 July 2008 \u2013 Olympia, London|publisher=IslamExpo|date=11 July 2008|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> In February and March 2009, he toured with other [[Anasheed|Nasheed]] artists, including [[Mecca2Medina]] and [[Poetic Pilgrimage]] on the \"I am [[Malcolm X]] Tour\".<ref name=\"britishhiphop\">{{cite news |last=(reporter) |first=Nino|url=http://www.britishhiphop.co.uk/news/latest/i_am_malcolm_x_tour.html|title=I Am Malcolm X Tour|publisher=British Hip Hop|date=18 February 2009|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"radicalmiddleway\">{{cite web|url=http://radicalmiddleway.co.uk/events/cultural-tour/i-am-malcolm-x|title=Radical Middle Way|date=7 October 2011|accessdate=1 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013352/http://radicalmiddleway.co.uk/events/cultural-tour/i-am-malcolm-x|archive-date=3 December 2013|url-status=dead}} I AM Malcolm X</ref> In 2009, he released ''From the Streets to Islam'', a CD in which he is being interviewed and responds to the questions by rapping. This was a preview to launching his first album.<ref name=\"muslimyouthskills\"/><ref name=\"nme\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.nme.com/nme-video/youtube/id/UK-6ji9m-HA|title=Muslim Belal- Be careful and fearful (Pray Hard album)|magazine=[[NME]]|date=August 2009|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> In the same month, a collaborative charity single \"Feed the World, Feed the Fasting\" was released by [[Muslim Aid]]. The song featured Chin along with artists [[Rizwan Hussain]], Abdullah Rolle, Khaleel Muhammad, Labbayk and [[Mecca2Medina]].<ref name=\"muslimaid\">{{cite web |url=https://www.muslimaid.org/media-centre/news/muslim-aids-exclusive-charity-nasheed-single/|title=Muslim Aid's Exclusive Charity Nasheed Single|publisher=Muslim Aid|accessdate=23 November 2014}}</ref> In October and November 2009, he supported Shaam on their UK tour.<ref name=\"audiencewithshaam\">{{cite web |url=http://www.audiencewithshaam.com/artists.html|title=Artists|publisher=An Audience with SHAAM|year=2009|accessdate=1 July 2012}} Muslim Belal</ref> Ashley Chin released his debut studio album ''[[Pray Hard]]'' on 15 August 2009 by Halal Dawa Records under his alias '''Muslim Belal'''. Chin's poetry combines spiritualism with social issues and his own personal history. The album features themes of repentance, his [[Religious conversion#Islam|conversion to Islam]], [[Naseeha|giving advice]], praising [[Allah]], preparations for the hereafter and [[Dua|supplicating to Allah]].<ref name=\"restlessbeings\"/>\n\n===2010\u20132014: ''The Transition and Victim''===\nIn October 2010, he performed at the Global Peace and Unity Event,<ref name=\"GPU010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theglobalunity.com/10/conference/artists-a-performers|title=Artists & Performers|publisher=Global Peace and Unity Event 2010|year=2010|accessdate=1 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903052739/http://www.theglobalunity.com/10/conference/artists-a-performers|archive-date=3 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> where he also launched his second album ''[[The Transition (album)|The Transition]]''. The album had a guest appearance from [[Lowkey]] and was released on 23 October 2010.<ref name=\"islamicimpressions\">{{cite web|url=http://www.islamicimpressions.co.uk/muslim-belal-the-transition.xhtml |title=Muslim Belal \u2013 The Transition |publisher=Islamic Impressions |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=1 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121219155003/http://www.islamicimpressions.co.uk/muslim-belal-the-transition.xhtml |archivedate=19 December 2012 }}</ref> In February 2011, Ashley Chin took his talents to the United States and performed at the Saint Louis University Muslim Student Association Annual Conference.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.slu.edu/organizations/msa/eventspast.php|title=Muslim Students' Association of Saint Louis University|website=www.slu.edu|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref> This performance was the first of its kind and developed an international audience.\n\nIn 2011, Chin co-wrote <ref name=\"raindance\">{{cite web |last=Bowman|first=Dean|url=http://www.raindance.co.uk/site/index.php?aid=7940|title=Victim|publisher=Raindance Film Festival|date=2 October 2011|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"variety1\">{{cite magazine |last=Lodderhose|first=Diana|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118048050|title=Kaleidoscope nabs 'Victim' in U.K.|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=3 January 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> and starred in ''[[Victim (2011 film)|Victim]]'' in a lead role with Michael Maris.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |last=Kermode|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.co.uk/film/2012/jun/24/victim-film-ashley-chin-review|title=Victim \u2013 review|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=24 June 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> On 22 June 2012, the film was released in UK cinemas.<ref name=\"tmpost\" /><ref name=\"kaleidoscopefilmdistribution\">{{cite web|url=http://kaleidoscopefilmdistribution.com/content/detail.asp?ID=20&title=Victim&origin=New|title=Victim|publisher=Kaleidoscope Film Distribution|year=2012|accessdate=1 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603124356/http://kaleidoscopefilmdistribution.com/content/detail.asp?ID=20&title=Victim&origin=New|archive-date=3 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The film also stars [[Ashley Madekwe]], [[Jason Maza]], and co-stars [[Adam Deacon]],{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} [[David Harewood]]<ref name=\"contactmusic\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/uk-film-mavericks-pure-film-productions-are-not-victims-of-their-own-success-after-payback-season_1320754|title=Uk Film Mavericks Pure Film Productions Are Not 'Victims' Of Their Own Success After Payback Season|magazine=[[Contactmusic.com|Contactmusic]]|date=20 April 2012|accessdate=1 June 2012}}</ref> and [[Giggs (rapper)|Giggs]]. The film is about a young man's attempts to move away from a life of violent crime, with the help of a wholesome country girl who comes to stay with his friend in the city, only to find himself the target of retaliation. Chin also had supporting roles in the shows ''[[Waking the Dead (TV series)|Waking the Dead]]'', ''[[Silent Witness]]''<ref name=\"bbcsilentwitness1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01pzqdb|title=Silent Witness, Series 16, Trust, Part 1|publisher=[[BBC One]]|date=17 January 2013|accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"radiotimessilentwitness1\">{{cite magazine |last=Butcher|first=David|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/tpmjj/silent-witness--series-16---3-trust---part-one|title=Silent Witness \u2013 Series 16 \u2013 3. Trust \u2013 Part One|magazine=[[Radio Times]]|date=17 January 2013|accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"silentwitness2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01pzqjk|title=Silent Witness, Series 16, Trust, Part 2|publisher=[[BBC One]]|date=18 January 2013|accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"radiotimessilentwitness2\">{{cite magazine |last=Butcher|first=David|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/tpvj2/silent-witness--series-16---4-trust---part-two|title=Silent Witness \u2013 Series 16 \u2013 4. Trust \u2013 Part Two|magazine=[[Radio Times]]|date=18 January 2013|accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> and ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''.<ref name=\"casualty\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2014/20/casualty|title=Casualty|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=17 May 2014|accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"radiotimescasualty1\">{{cite magazine |last=Brown|first=David|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/cv9kcs/casualty--series-28---37-games-for-boys|title=Casualty - Series 28 - 34. When Nothing Else Matters|magazine=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"radiotimescasualty2\">{{cite magazine |last=Brown|first=David|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/cv9kcs/casualty--series-28---37-games-for-boys|title=Casualty - Series 28 - 37. Games for Boys|magazine=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nChin had supporting roles in the 2011 films; ''[[Cherry Tree Lane]]''<ref name=\"salt\">{{cite news|url=http://www.salt-co.com/index.php/news/cherry-tree-lane-s-ashley-chin-selected-for-edinburgh-trailblazers|title=Cherry Tree Lane's Ashley Chin selected for Edinburgh trailblazers|publisher=Salt|date=12 June 2010|accessdate=1 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808041915/http://www.salt-co.com/index.php/news/cherry-tree-lane-s-ashley-chin-selected-for-edinburgh-trailblazers|archive-date=8 August 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"puremovies\">{{cite news|last=Rolland|first=Neil|url=http://www.puremovies.co.uk/reviews/cherry-tree-lane/|title=Cherry Tree Lane New Release|publisher=Pure Movies|date=11 September 2010|accessdate=1 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110301013937/http://www.puremovies.co.uk/reviews/cherry-tree-lane/|archive-date=1 March 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> and ''[[Anuvahood]]'',<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite news |last=Patterson|first=Joseph|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/urban/262723-anuvahood-film-premiere-the-review|title='Anuvahood' Film Premiere: The Review!|publisher=[[MTV (UK and Ireland)|MTV UK]]|date=18 March 2011|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> and also a cameo in ''[[Sket]]''.<ref name=\"film-book\">{{cite web |url=http://film-book.com/sket-2011-movie-trailer-movie-poster-nirpal-bhogal-aimee-kelly/|title=SKET (2011) Movie Trailer, Movie Poster: Nirpal Bhogal, Aimee Kelly|date=7 October 2011|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> He was also selected as the 2010 Trailblazer at the [[Edinburgh International Film Festival]] for the role of Asad in Cherry Tree Lane.<ref name=\"edfilmfest\"/><ref name=\"thebwhagency'\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebwhagency.co.uk/site2/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=34&Itemid=53|title=Film|publisher=The Braidford Willougby Hutton Agency|year=2012|accessdate=1 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221000201/http://www.thebwhagency.co.uk/site2/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=34&Itemid=53|archive-date=21 February 2012|url-status=dead}} Ashley Chin</ref> In April 2012, Chin co-starred in ''[[The Boxer (2012 film)|The Boxer]]'', a seven-minute short film, alongside [[Paul Barber (actor)|Paul Barber]]. The film was the winner for \"Project 7\"<ref name=\"bnctv\">{{cite news|last=Demsey|first=John|url=http://www.bnctv.co.uk/the-boxer-and-memory-lane-premiere-at-the-lexi-success|title='The Boxer' And 'Memory Lane' Premiere at the Lexi Success|publisher=BNCTV North West London|date=18 April 2012|accessdate=1 October 2012}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It was directed by Henry Blake, written by Daniel Bailey and produced by Scruffbag Productions. The film is about the relationship between a young man and his grandfather. It premiered on 17 April 2012 at the Lexi Cinema in [[Kensal Green|Kensal Rise]], London along with the runner-up of \"Project 7\", premiered during a special screening<ref name=\"brent\">{{cite web |url=http://www.brent.gov.uk/pressreleases.nsf/News/LBB-1777|title=Winners of Project 7 young film makers competition announced|publisher=Brent Council|date=2 April 2012|accessdate=2 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nFrom October to December 2012,<ref name=\"londontown\">{{cite web |url=http://www.londontown.com/LondonEvents/Damned-By-Despair/06258/|title=Damned By Despair|website= |location=London|publisher=LondonTown|date=August 2012|accessdate=1 December 2012}}</ref> he played the role of Escalante in [[Frank McGuinness]]'s ''Damned By Despair'', the English translated version of [[Tirso de Molina]]'s 1625 play ''El Condenado por Desconfiado'', at the [[Royal National Theatre]].<ref name=\"nationaltheatre\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/discover-more/artists/ashley-chin|title=Ashley Chin|publisher=National Theatre|date=August 2012|accessdate=1 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002232828/http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/discover-more/artists/ashley-chin|archive-date=2 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"thebwhagency2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebwhagency.co.uk/site2/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=466:ashley-chin&catid=36:theatre&Itemid=55|title=Ashley Chin|website=|publisher=The Braidford Willougby Hutton Agency|date=August 2012|accessdate=1 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101223103/http://www.thebwhagency.co.uk/site2/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=466:ashley-chin&catid=36:theatre&Itemid=55|archive-date=1 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"thestage4\">{{cite news |last=Paxman|first=Laura|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/37557/damned-by-despair|title=Damned by Despair|newspaper=[[The Stage]]|date=11 October 2012|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref> In October and November 2012, he was involved in filming of Destiny Ekaragha's adaptation of Bola Agbaje's play ''Gone Too Far''.<ref name=\"variety2\">{{cite news |last=Mitchell|first=Robert|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118060595|title=BFI, Poisson Rouge to back 'Gone Too Far'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=11 October 2012|accessdate=1 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"hollywoodreporter\">{{cite news |last=Kemp|first=Stuart|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/british-stage-play-gone-far-378183|title=British Stage Play 'Gone Too Far' to Hit Cinema Screens|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=10 October 2012|accessdate=1 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nFrom May to August 2013, he played the role of [[Mercutio]] in a National Theatre production of [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' in [[Ben Power]]'s version for young audiences.<ref name=\"derryjournal\">{{cite news |url=http://www.derryjournal.com/lifestyle/entertainment/romeo-and-juliet-world-premiere-in-waterside-1-5080155|title=Romeo and Juliet world premiere in Waterside|location=Derry|publisher=[[Derry Journal]]|date=10 May 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"derrycity\">{{cite news|url=http://www.derrycity.gov.uk/News/ROMEO-AND-JULIET#.UaEvNpxX1zN|title=ROMEO AND JULIET|location=Derry|publisher=Derry City Council|date=2 May 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025030611/http://www.derrycity.gov.uk/News/ROMEO-AND-JULIET#.UaEvNpxX1zN|archive-date=25 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"stage5\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/listings/production.php/60637/romeo-and-juliet|title=Romeo and Juliet|newspaper=[[The Stage]]|date=2 May 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, he performed at the Global Peace and Unity Event, where he launched his very best of compilation album ''Black Slave''.<ref name=\"tawheedisunity\"/><ref name=\"GPU13\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theglobalunity.com/performers/muslim-belal/|title=Muslim Belal|publisher=Global Peace and Unity|date=November 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203022446/http://www.theglobalunity.com/performers/muslim-belal/|archive-date=3 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> He also played a supporting roles in ''[[Fedz]]''<ref name=\"flavourmag2\">{{cite news |last=Allen|first=Annika|url=http://www.flavourmag.co.uk/q-the-man-behind-deadmeat-there-are-many-causalities-of-war-in-filmmaking-it-is-a-fierce-battle/|title=Q the man behind Deadmeat: \"There are many causalities of war in filmmaking, it is a fierce battle\"|publisher=Flavour Magazine|date=24 March 2011|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite news|last=Obenson|first=Tambay A.|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/poster-promo-for-brit-crime-thriller-fedz|title=Poster/Promo Trailer For Brit Crime Thriller 'FEDZ' (Ashley Walters, Joseph Marcell Co-Star)|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=1 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109012803/http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/poster-promo-for-brit-crime-thriller-fedz|archive-date=9 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and ''[[Starred Up]]'' during this time.<ref name=\"variety3\">{{cite magazine |last=Debruge|first=Peter|url=http://www.variety.com/2013/film/reviews/telluride-film-review-starred-up-1200594716/|title=Telluride Film Review: 'Starred Up'|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1 September 2013|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref> Chin starred and wrote in ''Pressure''. A short film released on Valentine's Day in 2014. It premiered through [[GRM Daily]].\n\n===2015\u2013present: ''My Sumaya and Faith''===\nChin released third album ''[[My Sumaya]]'' on 19 May 2015. It is a charity album with all the proceeds going towards feeding the most vulnerable children in Eastern [[Sudan]].<ref name=\"cdbaby\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/muslimbelal|title=My Sumaya|publisher=CD Baby|accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref> The album was named after his daughter.\n\nHe starred in the 2016 film ''The Intent'' alongside [[Scorcher (rapper)|Scorcher]], [[Krept and Konan]]. He reprised his role in the 2018 prequel ''The Intent 2: The Come Up'', released in 2018. The film also starred [[Ghetts]] and [[Popcaan]]. Chin also had a supporting role in [[EastEnders]]. Where he played the role of Sam in 2 episodes. After a year long hiatus from music, Chin released the single ''Life'' on 6 January 2019.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9690aGhZ1Ss</ref>\n\nChin worked with Giggs to write and release a short film in promotion of his album ''Wamp 2 Dem''. ''[[The Essence (film)|The Essence]]'' is a short film that was released on 12 April 2019 on Giggs' YouTube channel that is inspired by the soundtrack of ''Wamp 2 Dem''. It was written by Michael 'Buck' Maris, Ashley Chin and April Walker and directed by Myles Whittingham.  Chin also played a lead role in the film and Giggs makes a cameo appearance.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qqYm417B1O0</ref> Chin worked with Giggs before for the film ''Victim.\n\nAshley Chin released an autobiography titled ''Faith'' on October 2019. Chin stated that he learnt more from travelling the world than he did from school. Saying that \"I spoke about my life and changed peoples lives. Yesterday I was born, today I live, tomorrow I die. I put it all in a book for them to remember me by\". The following month in November 2019, Chin announced that he is directing and writing a movie based on the book. It is a [[coming of age]] story about a South London boy who finds faith in Islam to escape gang life. He travels to Egypt to find his faith in life again but he must return to keep a commitment to his best friend's, fatherless daughter and face the past.  Its a feature film based on the true story of Ashley Chins life. It follows the life of a young South London boy Ash, and his journey to finding the meaning in life and discovering the religion of Islam.<ref>https://www.shahaadahproductions.com/</ref> It stars [[Hope Ikpoku]], Keira Chansa and [[Fady Elsayed]] and is set to be released early 2020.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2002, at the age of 19, Chin [[Religious conversion#Islam|converted to Islam]].<ref name=\"islamicgarden\"/> In 2004,<ref name=\"msa\">{{cite web |url=http://msa.slu.edu/speakerbios.php#Belal|title=Speaker Biographies|publisher=Muslim Students' Association of Saint Louis University|date=28 January 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}} Brother Belal Ashley</ref> he travelled to [[Egypt]] and lived there for a year to study [[Islam]].<ref name=\"muslimyouthskills\"/>\n\nHis mother and elder sister have also converted to Islam.<ref name=\"tawheedisunityyoutube\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=72KMSBnZ9VI|title=Muslim Belal talks Islam and family|publisher=Tawheed Is Unity TV|date=18 October 2009|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> He is a [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United Football Club]] fan.\n\nIn June 2010, Chin performed [[Umrah]] (the second largest Islamic pilgrimage to [[Mecca]], [[Saudi Arabia]]).<ref name=\"RoadSide2Islamyoutube\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KgA89cnZVqM|title=Muslim Belal & Abubakr Islam \u2013 Live in the Holy City of Mecca \u2013 R2I Monthly Reminders|publisher=RoadSide2Islam|date=28 June 2010|accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref> Between July 2011 to May 2012, Chin resided in [[Kuwait City]], [[Kuwait]].\n\nIn July 2013, he appeared on [[Channel 4]]'s ''Ramadan Reflections''.<ref name=\"channel4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/4ramadan/videos/all/day-18-ashley-chin|title=Day 18: Ashley Chin|work=Ramadan Reflections|publisher=[[Channel 4]]|date=2 May 2013|accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref> In February 2014, Chin set up a charity ABC Life.<ref name=\"ABCLifeyoutube\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1vDQUGvhvHA|title=ABC Life \u2013 Ashley Belal Chin|publisher=ABC Life|date=18 February 2014|accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref> In June 2014, he visited [[Pakistan]] to deliver a lecture and record television interviews at Dreamworld Family Resort in [[Karachi]].<ref name=\"thepioneer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thepioneer.com.pk/british-rap-music-convert-comes-to-pakistan/|title=Muslim Belal Comes to Pakistan|date= 20 June 2014|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2010\n| ''[[Cherry Tree Lane]]''\n| Asad\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Supporting role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2011\n| ''[[Sket]]''\n| Titch\n|-\n| ''[[Anuvahood]]''\n| Mo\n|-\n| ''[[Victim (2011 film)|Victim]]''\n| Tyson\n| Lead role, writer and associate producer\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2012\n| ''[[The Boxer (2012 film)|The Boxer]]''\n| Michael\n| Lead role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 2013\n| ''[[Fedz]]''\n| Tyson\n| rowspan=\"7\"| Supporting role\n|-\n| ''[[Starred Up]]''\n| Ryan\n|-\n| ''Gone Too Far''\n| Mark\n|-\n| ''[[Plastic (2014 film)|Plastic]]''\n| Dion\n|-\n| ''[[Snow in Paradise]]''\n| Amjad\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2014\n| ''Money and Grime''\n| Valentine\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Intent]]''\n| G Money<ref name=\"Filmoria\">{{cite web |url=https://www.filmoria.co.uk/new-trailer-poster-for-the-intent-2-the-come-up/|title=New Trailer & Poster for THE INTENT 2: THE COME UP|date= 28 August 2018|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2018\n| ''[[The Intent 2: The Come Up]]''\n| G Money\n| Main role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2019\n| ''[[The Essence (film)|The Essence]]''\n| Isaac\n| rowspan=\"1\"| Lead role, also writer. Short YouTube film released by [[Giggs (rapper)|Giggs]] in promotion for his album.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2020\n| ''[[Faith (2020 film)|Faith]]''\n| {{na}}\n| rowspan=\"1\"| Director, writer and producer.\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\" align=\"center\"\n! Y